reviewText: And that's really not a good thing. The CGI in this movie is a joke. nearly every action scene features digitally rendered versions of the actors and it's not very high quality looking at all. The acting (or maybe it was the script?) was also equally laughable. Channing Tatum can't act to save his life! And that chick that played the Baroness? What the crap? She was pretty, but not pretty or exotic enough to convincingly play a character like that. When she first stepped off the enemy plane at the beginning of the movie, I almost laughed. She had on this low cut black top with these cheap looking sequins sewn around the neck line. I didn't really know what to make of that; it looked like some Kmart club outfit, certainly not something one would wear to kick butt. Dennis Quaid was equally horrific playing the big man in control of the GI Joe team. Nearly one handed, he really upped the cartoon quality on the movie. The role was completely ill suited for him. I sat all the way through it, but I would never do it again. And a sequel? Fuhgeddaboutit!! The Blu-ray quality is extremely nice with a robust soundtrack and perfectly pleasant picture, but it's hard to improve on what you're seeing and hearing when that's the way it was written and acted. I highly recommend giving this second rate action movie a rental before wasting hard earned money on it!
summary: Wow, It's Just Like the Cartoon...

reviewText: Short attention span summary (SASS):1. GI Joe goes global, hi-tech and impossibly awesome2. Bad guys include the standard megalomaniac with Gaelic accent, mad scientist, hot chick, martial arts expert  and a horde of nano-mites, capable of never-before-seen destruction unless someone hits the kill-switch3. Good guys include General with a heart of gold, hunky lead, comic relief sidekick, hot chick number 2, martial arts expert number 2, computer hacker and dependable strong arm guy.4. The plot obviously involves good guys trying to stop bad guys from unleashing havoc and mass destruction yada yada yada, amidst a maze of flashbacks and little snippets of snappy dialogue.5. Massive CGI and action extravaganza follows, including, but not limited to, easily accessible underground fortresses, a little cat fight, awesome weaponry, cool super-suits, planes, trains and automobiles, space age submarines, altered henchmen, a polar bear and the amazing sinking polar ice-cap.This movie may be totally inaccurate and impossible, but you can't fault the in-your-face non-stop action for light summer movie fare.  We may not always have Paris, but fans of improbable action movies should like this just fine.  Being capable of not thinking too much on a hot August afternoon, this was an enjoyable escape from reality.Amanda Richards, August 17, 2009

reviewText: 4 of 5 stars for the action movie G.I. Joe. OK, so I've lost touch with some of the new things... When you say GI Joe to me, I think of the action toy GI Joe with his circa WWII Jeep and uniform. I seem to have slept thru all of the various modernizations of GI Joe including the comic book, cartoon movies and newer toys. So, going into this movie, I had no expectatoins of what it would be. So, I've learned that the action toy has morphed into an elite military unit with sci-fi special weapons and tools. Only the elite become GI Joe's (men and women) who work out of "The Pit". This movie was very well made. Action from the first minutes to introduce the team during a firefight to protect a truck convoy. Next we find the hero of protecting that convoy is taken to the Pit and introduced to the team; after traning he becomes a GI Joe. The bulk of the movie was focused on the recovery of the item taken from that truck convoy and learning who was behnd the plot. Some good twists and unexpected things. Great action, wow sets and special effects that were seamless, the characters were a bit flat and 2-D hence the 4 stars. Oh, did I mention great action (yes, I did). This is a fun movie to watch and is worth a couple of bags of popcorn to enjoy. I do recommnd it. The blu-ray had sufficient behind-the-scenes contents on a second disk in the set, however, that disk and materials were on SD on a DVD; too bad, no HD extra contents. I do recommend this movie.
summary: GI Joe goes high-tech with great special effects

reviewerName: A.P. Fuchs, author of The Axiom-man Saga "www...
reviewText: When military partners Duke (Channing Tatum) and Ripcord (Marlon Wayans) get involved in the super covert ultra team G.I. Joe thanks to botching up supervising the delivery of nano-mite war-heads on behalf of the US Army, they join the team to try and track the war-heads down before they're unleashed on the world. To make things even more difficult for Duke, his ex-girlfriend, Anastasia "Ana" DeCobray (Sienna Miller), also the "Baroness," is part of the team responsible for stealing the nano-mite war-heads, and he is torn between trying to figure out what happened to her and also doing the right thing not just for his country, but for the whole world.Yet Duke and Ana aren't the only ones with a past. Opposing ninja warriors Snake Eyes (Ray Park) and Storm Shadow (Byung-hun Lee) go back to when they were children and trained under the same sensei. It wasn't until a tragic event in their youth drove the two apart, only to meet now, years later, and settle their conflict once and for all.With only the safety of the world resting in the hands of the best of the best of the best, team G.I. Joe has their work cut out for them as they try to save the world from the rising C.O.B.R.A.This movie is lightning. Seriously. Right from the first minute straight through to the last this sucker moves at breakneck speed with non-stop action, fireballs, lasers, bullets, super-powered armor, kung-fu, car chases, car crashes, aerial battles and a whole ton more.It's been awhile since I've seen a movie where I felt like I was moving at the speed of light and G.I. Joe delivers that in spades. I went in expecting an action movie. I got it. I went in expecting a military movie. I didn't get that but instead got something between the Avengers, Desert Storm and James Bond. It didn't feel like an army movie and for that I was thankful because, though I like history and military fiction, I have a hard time watching army movies. Don't know why. Just can't get into them. Also, all that olive green is nauseating after a while. Thank goodness that stupid color is absent in G.I. Joe. They wear black, thank you very much.The overall plot was cool. The problem was the pace. It was just way too fast. However, I was pleasantly surprised by the flashback sequences throughout the movie and even the fact the movie starts off in 1641 instead of the present day. More specifically, I was impressed the flashback sequences didn't happen to just one character, but to several, each segment adding to that character's history and giving us something more than a man or woman with an agenda. We actually get to understand their motivations because we get to be there with them and see how they came to be what they came to be.There was something else I had a hard time buying, but I'll leave it there because I don't want to spoil anything for those who haven't seen it yet.In the end, this film delivered a lot and truly embodied the idea of "rise of the cobra." There was origins galore, the ones not mentioned above being Destro and the Doctor. There will no doubt be a sequel because there's obviously way more story to tell.Rating this film was tough because there's no way to be critical of it without coming off unfair. I mean, really, the effects were 5 out of 5. No challenge there. The explosions alone were awesome never mind the Eiffel Tower falling, the nano-mite green mist effect, those blue electro pulses--craziness. The story? Well . . . how's 3 sound? Yeah? Okay. Tell you what: I'll meet you halfway and we'll settle on 4. Cool? Cool.Oh and one more thing . . .Go Joe!A.P. Fuchs
summary: This Movie is One Big, Crazy Adrenaline Rush!

reviewText: Ok, first of all I loved the look of this movie and the idea of GI Joe.  Having grown up watching the cartoons and playing with the toys, I have to say that this and transformers were the two most anticipated movies of the year for me....although in the end bothAngels & Demons (Two-Disc Extended Edition)andStar Trek (Two-Disc Digital Copy Edition)stole the year for me.From an adult's perspective, I'll tell you why:- Transformers 2 was a big giant advertisement for the US Armed Forces (every war machine in the US arsenal was featured)- GI Joe was a big giant advertisement for the United Nations (very eerie)I can understand Hasbro's dilema, GI Joe was marketed in the US but it was also sold in the UK, Germany, France etc so they had to give it a more worldly treatment.  There were rumors the Joes would be HQed in Belgium (big no no from my side) and in the end they wind up being based somewhere in Africa.  With technology available today, I think they could've easily done 5 movies with the Joe's HQed in whatever country the movie was released in (why not?).The other thing that detracted from the Joes for me was that the action sequences were eeriely similar to the Transformers scenes. In one scene the Joes are running down some street and they have this slow motion leap where they're dodging bullets and debris.  I swear that was the same scene from Transformers where the Transformers do the exact same contorted leaks (did they just replace transformers for Joes and use the same CGI rendering code?)  I wonder.So at the end of the day, I have to say that the movie breaks down as follows for me:PROS- great special effects (on par with Transformers, feels like they used the same CGI artists)- Dennis Quaid (I'm a big fan)- fast paced story- cool special effects (worth saying twice)CONS- embedded political ideologies- shallow character development (except for the ninjas - that was good)Agewise:- if you're between 10 and 18 this movie is probably just great- if you grew up with GI Joe, you'll probably enjoy but you'll likely see the politicsOverall, I enjoyed the GI Joe Movie but I had a real hard time getting beyond the political propaganda being peddled.  In the end for a grown guy like me, Star Trek and Angels and Demons were more entertaining but hey, I'm an old guy.  If you're young, probably transformers and GI Joe were where it's at....but definitely give Star Trek a try.At the end of the day Star Trek was the best movie of the year, albeit it has its own set of political ideologies embedded in it.

reviewText: When I saw the trailer with the power-suits running through traffic, it turned me off. Because it didn't look like GI JOE. It looked like a teenage boy thing--which is what I suppose GI JOE is supposed to be--plus throw in stuff for us old timers that actually saw the cartoons and read the comics back in the day.The movie thankfully keeps itself PG-13 where it should be and just has fun. There are a ton of characters in it and so the scripting is actually pretty good considering. There are lots of connections here--like, why are they blasting through Paris? Well, it was the French that made Destro, and his decendent wanted revenge. The little and the big are all wrapped up neatly. Throw in unexpected fun moments like Bendan Fraser as a JOE, some great lines ("Nice shoes."), and a great character triangle with Duke, the Baroness and Cobra Commander, and as a whole the movie just works. This is a good, solid update to the franchise.Why did I give it a chance? Well, I saw the preview for the next GI JOE movie--and it's supposed to have Bruce Willis as the original JOE. Are you kidding? That was reason enough for me to give this film a chance. It stands well on it's own and I can't wait for the next installment.
summary: Didn't watch it after seeing the trailers, but finally gave it a spin

reviewText: To be fair, I've two conflicting viewpoints on this film. One is that of the adult filmgoer who's seen more than his fair share of cinema and can look at this film as nothing more than another summer action film. The other viewpoint is that of the nine-year-old boy who had a room full of G.I. Joe toys and watched the cartoon show everyday after school back in the 80s. I'll give reviews for both viewpoints.*For the non-Joe fans:If you're not a fan or have no prior knowledge of the 1980s G.I. Joe franchise, chances are this is a movie you can skip in the theaters. A few great action sequences aside, it'll likely be a film that has more cons than pros for you.  If you're going into this film for just a straight up good action flick you'll likely be disappointed with the horrible acting, spastic editing, overly clichéd moments, and mediocre directing. A "C" grade (2  star) film at best.*For the Joe Fans:As a longtime fan I walked out of G.I. Joe feeling like the film had some really great parts, but as a whole it didn't reach its potential. The main element that turned me off as a long time Joe fan was the way Storm Shadow & Snake Eyes were handled. They had what I'm sure were pretty spectacular sword fights, but I couldn't tell because of all the ridiculous close ups and jump cuts! Plus the two brief flashbacks handling their history together were just plain awful.Surprisingly the Baroness character turned out to be the most interesting part of the film. She was a much more fully realized character than her animated counterpart and she was perhaps the most sympathetic and well rounded character in the entire film. I thought the plot of the film was actually pretty good. They made a really plausible prequel for the 80s cartoon show. Well, as plausible as one can get for an 80s cartoon show. As the title implies, this film is all about how Cobra is formed. And it does a fairly decent job of explaining why so many capable people followed the weak and almost inept leader of Cobra in the cartoon show as well as how the iconic characters of Destro, Zartan, Baroness, Storm Shadow, Dr. Mindbender, and Cobra Commander all came together. Also for fanboys wondering about the absent Cobra logo, towards the very end of the film we get a brief underwater glimpse of it.Speaking of the ending, this will likely be a BIG controversy for Joe fans and geeks in general. I won't go into spoiler territory here, but I will say it's basically a combination of the endings of Star Wars Episodes I & IV. No, seriously. My friends and I were having a blast pointing out all the "lifted" shots and similar moments between the films. Personally I thought it was fun and meant to be kind of obvious (because it really is obvious), a geeky bit of cross-pollinating cinema if you will. However, I can understand how some fans will take this as a "rip-off" and be angered they paid to see G.I. Joe movie but got a bootlegged version of a Star Wars ending instead.The film was obviously set up as the first in a franchise and there is room for improvement as they add some more classic Joe characters and hopefully get a better director to helm the franchise. The 80s nostalgia driven fan in me gives this flawed yet fun attempt at realizing a beloved childhood cartoon as live-action cinema a grade of B+ (3  stars).
summary: 3.5 stars for the Joe fans 2.5 stars for everyone else

reviewText: I never watched the cartoon as a child or collected the dolls/toys either so I can't tell you how this movie stacks up compared to past works, what I can tell you is I went to see this movie yesterday not expecting much and was pleasantly surprised at what I did see. I was afraid not having been a fan I would not be able to follow what was going on, however this is more of an origin film and they do a great job of walking noobs like me through it. I had a blast watching this movie from start to finish, and this movie had some of the coolest action sequences I've seen this year.Here is a brief plot synopsis, the movie takes place in the not too distant future where weapons expert James McCullen played by Christopher Eccleston has created a weapon that uses nanotechnology to basically eat through anything including whole cities. He sells four of these warheads to NATO, and Duke played by Channing Tatum and Ripcord played by Marlon Wayans are soldiers in the U.S. army  and are tasked with delivering the warheads. During the mission the pair are ambushed by the Baroness played by Sienna Miller, however they are saved by Scarlett played by Rachel Nichols, Snake Eyes played by Ray Park, and Heavy Duty played by Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje  members of a secret black ops group known as the Joes.They are then taken back to The Pit the Joe's command center in North Africa. Here Duke, and Ripcord convince General Hawk played by Dennis Quaid to let them join the team for this mission as they know the Baroness personally from the past.The rest of the movie is a battle between the Joes and the double crosser James McCullen and his group of genetically altered soldiers over these warheads. There are some amazing fights in this movie I especially like the scenes with Sanke Eyes who's like some kind of super ninja and his rival Storm Shadow played by Lee Byung-hun. The whole car chase scene in France was amazing as well. This movie definitely snuck up on my top five movies of the year list, I'm going to give it a 4 out of 5 and would definitely recommend seeing it on the big sreen, to anyone who likes a good action flick.
summary: Never watched cartoon, but like this for what it is

reviewText: GOOD guys use bullets, knives, swords, grenades, and exploding eyeball harpoons, all to their full effect.  BAD guys use noise guns that shoot noise at people, which pushes them backwards, and sometimes makes them do backflips.The GOOD guys decapitated at least three people, and stabbed two different people in the eyeball (not counting the three eyeball-harpoonings).  The BAD guys tried to dissolve the Eiffel Tower.  The GOOD guys made it stop dissolving halfway through, which made it tumble over and crush a bridge full of people.Later a good guy got one of the noise guns, and it had a lock-on function, so Destro must have invented heat-seeking noise.  Unfortunately he had to stop using it when it evidently ran out of noise.The Baroness is haunted by memories of the best picnic ever.  It's unclear whether she ever did anything else with Duke, or if they just had the one late-afternoon picnic and then got engaged, but I wouldn't be surprised if that picnic was enough to seal the deal.  It was such an incredible picnic that the mere memory of it gave the Baroness strength to reject her evil nano-machine programming/infection.Cobra Commander: This injection deactivates people's self-preservation instinct.Destro: In ENGLISH please!Cobra Commander: They feel no fear.First of all, I've heard lots of complicated, confusing pseudo-science that makes another character say "in ENGLISH please!" in movies, and this was the least-complicated and least-confusing.  I think Destro might be stupid.  Second of all, three minutes later two of the fearless guys fell off something tall and screamed all the way down.Channing Tatum utilized the "Palin Method" in his portrayal of Duke (so called after the blogger/actress/former governor).  This method is identified by a dull, vacant look in the eyes.The G.I. Joes cussed a lot less when I was a kid.I'd say this would be a good movie for kids, except for all the eyeball-stabbings, head-explodings, and profanity-speakings.  Plus about a quarter of the movie is montages of two little boys beating and stabbing one another while an old pervert watches.  I'd say it's so bad that it's good for a laugh, if they trimmed it down by about seven hours.  As it stands, this is one of the worst movies I've ever seen in my life, and two of my favorite movies are Jean-Claude Van Damme vehicles.

reviewText: ***WARNING, SOME SPOILERS***Growing up in the 80's and being a huge cartoon fan, G.I Joe had to be up there as one of your top shows. So being that Joe fan growing up in the 80's and knowing that a movie  was being made upon it gave you something to look forward to until its release. Being a spectator of this film after having high hopes can be damaging to your health, and everything that you can remember from the cartoon show; in other words childhood memory.I will notate the flaws from this movie that made my stomach twitch: The dialogue and the ridiculous script that made look the Joe's (America's most badass!) like amateurs.The dialogue reminded me alot of what is considered one of the worst movie ever made: Batman & Robin. Cheesey lines, and unneccesary gags. In the movie theater you would hear dead silence when one of the characters 'tried' to be 'funny'. Even I felt ackward.I also hated the fact that the Cobras found so easily the Joe's their underground layer. Yes I know, there was a chip inside the suit case which is the only possible way of initiating such search but it was just too unreal and too easy. The writers could of thought of something better.Now, for the good things. Obviously the special effects, very well done, as well with the action sequences. Used to watch the 80's cartoon I found it quite astonishing how they pulled that one off.Snake Eyes steals the show for sure. He was my favorite character from the cartoon series and I can say that he is my favorite character from the movie. The female cast was also an eye candy, and I think them and Snake Eyes are the only reason why I would watch this movie again.If they are planning to make a sequel please make it less childish and remember that us real G.I Joe fans are actually adults. I was hoping for a more serious atmosphere and for an adult action movie. Kids probably left the theater happy and cheering while most of us grown ups left disappointed. It's not a bad film, it is entertaining but it does have its flaws that without them could of been far superior. I sure hope there's improvement for Part 2.
summary: It could of been way better!!!

reviewText: I had heard a lot of bad stuff about G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra and it was, for the most part, a bad rap. Sure, it wasn't set back in the 60's when G.I. Joe was founded, but World War 2 and Vietnam movies have been done to death. So, it was refreshing to see them take G.I. Joe in a completely different direction. The future. With new weapons, new technology and new faces.Sure the script has been criticized as being non-existent and smothered by action sequences and special effects. Yet, G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra is by far, a more creative and involving story than many actions movies of recent, as in, anything by Roland Emmerich, Twilight movies or whatever. It actually is a fast and furious pace with an actually very complicated story. That to me, was the problem. Because the fast and furiuos pace would brush over the story elements with a very thin brush and so when the ending finally got there, there were way too many loose ends and they all seemed to come pouring down in the final 3 minutes.They could have slowed down and made the story elements more important, but all in all, what you get with G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra is an energetic, cyber-weapon summer flick that gave people what most summer movie viewers want, slam bam action with cool effects.If anything, G.I. Joe tried to do TOO MUCH story, and didn't cover all of it or give it justice because they were more interested in pleasing the teenage crowd that buys the tickets. People like me, a 40-year old male who likes that stuff too, but would rather save his money to get by on bills, enjoyed the heck out of it in his living room with some surround sound and some Orville Redenbacker.
summary: Solid Movie with a hyperactive ending

reviewText: Back in June, a rumor was spread amongst Hollywood insiders stating that the director of "G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra," Stephen Sommers, was fired from the project and locked out of the editing room after a test screening received the lowest score of any Paramount Pictures test screening. I have no way of knowing whether or not this is true. On the basis of the final product, however, I tend to think that it might be. This movie is painfully bad, a nonstop, aggressive, ear splitting, eye straining explosion of action and special effects. It has a plot in the strictest sense, but in terms of delivery and execution, it never bothers to tell a story. It's a hopped up assault on the senses, the audience constantly bombarded with loud, hyperactive sequences of mindless violence and destruction. I enjoy summer popcorn flicks as much as the next guy, but I find them much more tolerable if they pause and take a deep breath every so often.I don't pretend to know anything about the original Hasbro action figures; my personal toy preference tended towards building sets and blank sheet of paper for drawing. From what I know, however, the original G.I. Joe figures were based on the American military and divided into actual branches like Army, Navy, and Air Force. They eventually shifted into a more action oriented back story involving the evil Cobra Command, and I guess that's what the movie is based on. So what we have is not so much a military story but a science fiction shoot-`em-up featuring a lot of cool special effects. If eye candy is your thing, fine, but don't expect to get anything out of the story. Incidentally, I use the word "story" loosely since it's pretty hard to figure out what this movie is about.At best, I can say that it involves specially engineered warheads filled with microscopic robots that can eat entire cities on a molecular level. Fighting over control of the warheads are the evil MARS corporation and a top secret military faction known as G.I. Joe. From the MARS corporation, we have the duplicitous weapons expert James McCullen (Christopher Eccleston), the smoking hot Baroness (Sienna Miller), the stealthy Storm Shadow (Lee Byung-hun), and master of disguise Zartan (Arnold Vosloo), who can never stop whistling "For He's a Jolly Good Fellow." There's also a mad doctor who looks like a cross between Freddy Kruger and Darth Vader, but I don't think I should reveal who plays him since that would give away a crucial plot point.From G.I. Joe, we have two recruited soldiers, Duke (Channing Tatum) and Ripcord (Marlon Wayans), the team leader, General Hawk (Dennis Quaid), the mute Snake Eyes (Ray Park), the hulking Heavy Duty (Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje), and the super-intelligent Scarlett (Rachel Nichols), who, much like a Vulcan, believes that emotions are useless because they can't be explained logically. Funny, given the fact that Nichols was also cast in this year's version of "Star Trek."We're introduced to all of these characters, and we're told a fair amount about their personal lives: Duke and Baroness were once engaged; Ripcord is falling in love with Scarlett; McCullen had an ancestor who was tried for treason in France back in 1641, which is when the film begins; the mad doctor knows more about Duke and Baroness than he cares to admit. But what does any of this mean? Not a heck of a lot, given the fact that most of what we're told plays second fiddle to the action. My God, the action--endless scenes of running and falling and jumping and shooting and punching and kicking and flying, and all of it saturated with CGI. Of all the things I gathered from this movie, the most prominent is that Sommers really has a thing with stuntmen projected through sheets of glass. That, and the fact that he must have had a burning desire to watch the Eiffel Tower get destroyed.If there is a saving grace for "G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra," it's that it manages to get better as it goes along. I still couldn't figure out what was going on, but at least I began getting involved. Of course, that's the point at which the movie ends, so I was ultimately left feeling completely unsatisfied. Who are these characters? What are they doing? Why should anyone even care?Some of you probably feel that I'm being too harsh on this film, especially since it isn't supposed to be anything more than summer entertainment. If you're one of them, here's what I have to say: Why should movies get a pass simply for being released during the summer? Why can't a good movie be good and a bad movie be bad, regardless of the season? I enjoy escapist entertainment as much as the next person, but when your movie can't take a couple of minutes to slow down and give the audience's eyes and ears a rest, you no longer have a movie. You have a noisy video game projected on a screen. "G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra" is exactly like that, and what's worse, the filmmakers never give the audience the controller and let it have a turn.
summary: An Action-Packed Action Film with Lots of Action

reviewText: Let me say first that I did not buy this film - I downloaded it in HD.  I am glad that I did not blind buy this one!!  When I heard that they were making a G.I. Joe live action film I said "it's about time!"  When I saw the promo pics of Snake Eyes, I thought that it looked promising - until I saw the first trailer.  Once I saw that I said this does not look right.  Rip Cord? He was not a major character!Once I heard that Marlon Wayans and Dennis Quaid would be in it I was not feeling good.  Wayans is about jokes and Quaid does not look athletic.  I had this on my PC since it was first released and I just got around to watching it.  That bad feeling that I had came true.  First is the Destro's ancestor scene which was not needed.  If they felt the need to go back in time, it should have been for Cobra Commander if anything.  The Destro character clearly wears a mask because he is the 'enemy weapons supplier' and does not want to be identified.Well, aside from the lack of a coherent story that seems like scenes were filmed and put together to hope that they get a movie, the script is horrible!  I rarely talk badly about most film's scripts (except B movies), but this script is one of the worst ever!  Why have Hawk say "knowing is half the battle?"  That was from the cartoon, not the G.I. Joe universe. They should not have even thought about the cartoon (although it seems as if the makers just watched one episode and felt that they got the gist of it), they should have just made their own vision of it.I always wondered what if they made a Transformer film and a G.I. Joe film, what would they look like?  I expected The Transformers to look stupid and I expected G.I. Joe to look serious.  Who would have thought that the film that would be harder to make convincing looked and was better, but the easier one was the one that looked foolish and corny?  The actors act as if they know the script sucks, but they are saying it anyway.  None of the actors look like they are least was put into some basic training and discipline.  They never stand like soldiers, act like soldiers or conduct themselves like soldiers.  Instead, they all look like actors dressed like soldiers.Since when did G.I. Joe have foreign soldiers?  Roadblock surly was not British and i do not recall Breaker being Moroccan let alone a main character - especially after Dial-Tone came along.  Also, Duke was a Master Sargent not a lieutenant. Hawk was a Brigadier General not a four star general.  I suppose they changed ranks in order to make it more believable that Duke would be the ground leader even is some Joe members out-ranked him and were officers.  The only time I can recall that this got addressed was in G.I. Joe:The Movie when Falcon said to Duke "I'm pulling rank!"  Some of us actually paid attention to the ranks, names and positions of the figures...Let me just say that this movie is horrible and I hope that they do not make a sequel.  If they do, PLEASE get someone else to do EVERYTHING on this film.  hell, REBOOT this one now.  i do not know how they messed this up when it should of had a focus on military instead of the cartoon or anything else that did not go together.  Not good.  Also, who cares about Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow fighting?  The did not start out as brothers and Snake Eyes did not start out as a martial artist, he just have the black commando suit and then they turned it into a ninja thing which helped ruin the toy line.I guess the makers felt that they should throw everyone in a black suit because black always looks cool and dangerous?  G.I. Joe was an AMERICAN thing (although the toys were released internationally but as native to those countries), but they put all of these foreigners in there.  Maybe some people are correct when they say that those who run the Federal Reserve are softening us up for a one world government with all of these British people on American movies, TV shows (tell me when have you seen this in US history?) and worst of all - our NEWS and politics shows!  As you can see from the cover, they thought that Snake Eyes was the selling point.  He was a cool character (mainly the Darth Vader effect with black), but I doubt that he was everyone's main attraction, although his figure was hard to find in stores.I felt NOTHING for any of the characters.  Hawk did not look strong or like a solider.  I think that the production team thought of this as toy line instead of it being a military thing. I did not care about ninjas, Cobra or G.I. Joe! It was also stupid for the director to have the characters be called their called names from the start of their lives.  Their names are code names not real names! This ruined my great memories of that toy line!  Stick to the cartoon as that was waaaaaaaaaaay better than this film!  This is one to stay away from and is not even worth a rental.  I now you will be hard headed and buy it anyway, but trust me...

reviewText: G.I. JOE: THE RISE OF COBRASTARRING: Channing Tatum, Marlon Wayans, Sienna Miller, Christopher Eccleston, Dennis Quaid, Rachel Nichols, Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Ray Park, Jonathan Pryce, Byung-hun Lee, Arnold Vosloo, Kevin J. O'Connor and Brendan FraserWRITTEN BY: Stuart Beattie, David Elliot, Paul Lovett, Michael Gordon and Stephen SommersDIRECTED BY: Stephen SommersRated: PG-13Genre: Action / Science FictionRelease Date: 07 August 2009You know it's a bad movie when Marlon Wayans is out-acting everyone on screen. Maybe the other actors of G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra, were trying to portray the action figure version G.I. Joes rather than the characters they play in the film. Their performances are every bit as lifeless as the plastic toys.Channing Tatum plays the central character named Duke, who is all about fighting and is a hard-core solider to the bone. But there is a huge flaw with his character. If he's such an awesome soldier, I'm sure he would know to address Generals as sir, wouldn't he? Not in this film. Apparently it's okay for him to cop an attitude towards them as well. Tatum is normally fun to watch but his performance in this film was terrible.Marlon Wayans plays Ripcord. Despite his ridiculous name, he was the only thing keeping my entertainment level from completely plummeting during the course of the film. He was a real-live person; he was believable and hilarious, as to be expected. He had some very good laugh-out loud one liners.The two of them must have joined in the buddy program because they have been together through every moment of their military careers side by side.The Plot? The two are transporting some warheads from A to B when they are ambushed by Duke's ex fiancé Anastasia (Sienna Miller) who wants them for evil. They are then rescued by the G.I. Joes; a special elite military team headed by General Hawk (Dennis Quaid). Immediately Duke wants in and Ripcord of course follows.Then there are some more bad guys, who want to take over the world for various reasons. There are a good ninja and a bad ninja who have some issues to discuss regarding their troubled childhood together. Oh yeah, and then one of the bad guys turns out to be an old friend of Duke's and the brother of Duke's ex-girlfriend, Anastasia and now none of them like each other because Duke was supposed to look after the brother, but then the brother supposedly was killed in action, so the sister was angry with Duke and vanished and died her hair black and got all dark and scary. But then the brother wasn't dead after all; only injured badly in an explosion, so now he is angry as well and wants to take over the world. Did you get all of that? It feels a little more like a daytime soap opera than one of the biggest action movies of the year doesn't it? Maybe they should have all went on the Dr. Phil show or to a group therapy session or something, to work out these issues and they could have saved all of us seven dollars and 100 minutes of our lives.I have been a huge fan of Stephen Sommers' work in the past. The Mummy, Deep Rising and Van Helsing are all among favorites of mine.With directing this film however, It seems like his goal may have been to use the most CGI (computer graphic imagery) ever. The man CGI'd everything! Water was CGI, underwater shots were CGI, sand was CGI, snow was CGI and even an Air Craft Carrier was CGI! Why? I just watched a low budget straight to DVD movie the other day and they were able to get footage of a live Carrier, so why wasn't this film able to do the same with its massive budget?It's bad enough that so many things were fake to begin with, but most of it was horribly done. There is a weapon in the film that releases this green gas, and takes down the Eiffel Tower. You can see it on any of the trailers. The tower was the only Computer Generated Image that was done well but the green gas looks so fake! I have seen video games and lower budget films with way better computer graphics. The water looked fake, snow looked fake and the sand looked really fake. Why were all of these things computer generated at all? You would think of all people, the guy who directed The Mummy would know where and how to get his hands on some real sand! I guess I shouldn't be too surprised though. After all, he did CGI The Rock in The Mummy Returns. I wished he hadn't returned.Let's talk about the costumes for a second. I understand that this was a T.V show and that the action figures were the most popular of all. I get all that. But if you look at the X-Men films, they enhanced the costumes in the movies to look, how should I put this... not so LAME. The `multi-million' dollar suits that Tatum and Wayans are running around the streets of Paris with were absolutely ridiculous looking. It reminded me of Arnold Schwarzenegger dressed as Turbo Man at the end of Jingle All the Way. That was a comedy, so what's G.I. Joe's excuse?From what I have heard, rather it's true or not I'm not sure, the film didn't even raise a profit at the box office. Despite this, rumor has it a sequel is already in the works. Upon hearing this information my brain could only muster a single response: G.I. wonder why they would do that.
summary: G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra Review

reviewText: The main problem with G.I. JOE: THE RISE OF COBRA?  It's not a G.I. JOE movie.  At all.  Somewhere along the way, the studio probably decided (correctly, it seems) that they could tack the G.I. JOE label on this baby and make a few extra bucks.  This story line could be told with any characters, and it would still make no sense whatsoever.Let's face it: you don't watch films like this for the story, the plot, the acting, the dialogue, or anything that you would watch a decent movie for.  You watch it for cheesy lines, lots of action...basically something to watch while eating nachos and drinking beer.  And, on that level, God help us all, THE RISE OF COBRA works.I won't bother rehashing the plot; there isn't one.  There's a whole lot of miscasting--Marlon Wayans? Really?--and way, way too many flashbacks; we don't care about Snake-Eyes's past, we only care about how much a** he kicks in the present (and, thanks to Ray Parks, he kicks a lot).  There's too much back story between Duke (Channing Tatum, as reliably wooden as always) and the Baroness (Sienna Miller, slumming it hardcore), and eventually a showdown between Duke, Cobra-to-be Rex (Joseph Gordon-Levitt), and Destro-to-be McCullen (Christopher Eccleston) involving who loves the Baroness the most (did I just ruin things?).  Yeah, even for an action-and-no-brains flick, it's far-fetched.  And don't get me started on the excelerator suits.But there's something to be said for actors who know they're making a horrible movie.  Gordon-Levitt is a pure and under delight, hamming it up almost as much as he did in (a far superior film) KILLSHOT; Eccleston is pure and utter camp, as is Dennis Quaid as the leader of the Joes.  We also get cameos from Sommers mainstays Brendan Fraser and Kevin J. O'Connor, and you know you're watching crap when you think to yourself: "This film could use more Brendan Fraser."  Fraser's MUMMY nemesis Arnold Vosloo is grossly under-used as Zartan, Cobra's shape-shifting wild card, as is Jonathan Pryce as the U.S. president.  Ultimately, we are left with a movie that means little or nothing to those of us who grew up with G.I. JOE, but is still valuable as mindless action schlock that appeals as a 2-hour distraction from reality.
summary: It's loud and proud...but what did you expect?

reviewText: This was a decent movie despite what many naysayers may say about it. While it's not a terrible film, but it does serve well as an intro story to those uninitiated in the world that is known as G.I. Joe. A pre-Magic Mike, Tatum Channing stars as Duke and Marlon Wayans as Ripcord. Dennis Quaid has a small role as General Hawk and Darth Maul himself, Ray Park plays Snake-Eyes, whose action scenes are awesome! Joseph Gordon Levitt also stars here as Rex Lewis, later known as Cobra Commander. Mummy alum Arnold Vosloo plays Zartan and Sienna Miller as the Baroness. The movie was directed by Stephen Sommers, who also directed The Mummy films with Vosloo and Brendan Fraser (who has a small cameo in Joe headquarters).As long as you don't take it too seriously, you should enjoy it for the entertainment value alone.

reviewText: There's only one scene of gruesome violence. The actors have decent chemistry. The sets are imaginative. The story is entertaining enough. I would even call GI Joe more science fiction then anything else. This is a fun B-movie, something safe enough for even older children to enjoy.Sure, GI Joe gets most of it's ideas from much better movies like the Matrix, X-Men and the Manchurian Candidate. So I realize it would be easy to tear a film like GI Joe to pieces! But the story made me laugh, at times, for being so preposterous. And, it was entertaining without going overboard. What's more New York City gets a reprieve, for a change, and was not attacked by the terrorists! What more could you ask for from this kind of movie?

reviewText: I have to say I was simply fascinated watching "GI Joe: The Rise of Cobra". Not because it was a good movie, or because it was innovative or original. "GI Joe" is simply amazing in that it fails at almost everything it tries to deliver.Action - I will give the movie a couple stars here, there are plenty of action scenes with things blowing up and bullets (and funky looking electricy blobs too) being shot almost constantly. Throw in some techno-matrix-karate fighting and a couple "Iron Man"-like super suits and you'll be distracted for a few minutes.Plot - Are you kidding? I love the idea of a metal-eating "virus" and the visual of seeing it hit the Eiffel Tower was pretty cool, but the mish-mash of a soldier feeling he let down the girl he loved, haunted by a failed mission..blah, blah, blah. We've seen it all before and it's a pretty thin stretch to make this the backbone of your film(this same plot device is actually the basis for the comedy "Airplane!"). At one point our hero shows up at a funeral in a thunderstorm...on a motorcycle...wearing sunglasses. Okay, I have an easier time buying the bionic super-suit and the Borg-like bad-guy than I do believing anyone would think its a good idea to go for a motorcycle ride in a driving rain wearing sunglasses, arriving while the funeral is in progress just so you can look all melancholy and cool.Special Effects - The big F/X moments in the flick actually pay off. The underwater villain's lair, the metal eating munchies going after the tanks and the tower look great. Unfortunately not as much attention seemed to be paid to the "little" things, like the CGI chase scenes where everything looked too cartoonish and simply silly.Cast - I'm convinced there were no actual humans in this film. Not one person "acted", they simply walked around looking good in several costumes, kind of like ninja-models-on-the-loose. You have to worry when the one character who doesn't utter a word the entire film and is hidden behind a mask actually manages to out-act everyone around him. Quite a menagerie of cliches too; the witty black side-kick who provides the comic relief (kept waiting for him to say "dayyyummm"), the drone like henchman, the Asian karate expert, the fat karate master. The "Real American Hero" thing is gone as well, now "GI Joe" is made up of soldiers from aound the globe...which is fine...except that the film basically focuses on only the American "GI Joe" characters...and the only "foreigners" are the bad guys.I know, I know, people are going to say.."what did you expect from a movie made out of a toy, and based on an 80's cartoon?". I simply have to say that I expected more than this. I never liked "The Transformers" cartoon (I was more of a Gobots kids myself) but I enjoyed the first film.Like "Van Helsing" and "The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen" & "The Hulk", "GI Joe" seems to mis-fire on most aspects and will be forgotten by the time the "Boom Boom Pow" finishes rolling during the closing credits.
summary: Jaw Dropping Stupidity on Almost Every Level

reviewText: The movie looks good and sounds good. It is fast paced from beginning to end. Yes, it won't likely win the actors any Oscars, but who was really expecting that kind of movie here anyways. I love the Dark Night and other serious adeptations of old comics/cartoons but there is still room for some over the top explosions and a plot with no real basis in reality. In fact having a 5 year old of my own and getting him the old cartoon series (which in my memory I held in very high esteem), I can safely say that it wasn't filled with a lot of believabilty, plot lines, or great voice acting. In fact the plots were often cheesy as was the sexual tension between some of the male and female characters. Ditto for the movie.  And if I am somewhat disappointed in the movie it is only in that the violence is a little bit much for the crowd they are marketing all those toys to. As an adult, I was OK with it and thought it fit what I wanted but as a parent watching it with my son I thought it was a bit much (the old cartoons were kid of like McGyver and the A-team in that about 10,000 rounds were expelled per episode yet no one on either side died). If you are a purist I think that would be about your only gripe as the rest of the movie I think nails the old cartoon. So sit back and watch stuff blow up for two hours, no harm in that.
summary: Entertaining albiet a bit graphic for young kids.

reviewText: How novel, a movie about a toy.  Why does that premise sound so silly?Talk about overkill!  Yeah it sparkled, all glitzy with gizmos and explosions and nasty nano-green goo and explosions and fire and....did I mention explosions?  I suppose they thought that if they kept things moving at a heady clip no one would notice there wasn't any substance beneath the KABOOM!  That all the actors were subordinate to the action and the, well, toy weapons and whatnot.  They really didn't need actors, they could have gotten by with robots (there was that one guy you couldn't see beneath his suit, didn't say a word, which was a blessing considering the dialog involved, was he a robot?  Couldn't tell.).  And then there was Sergeant Stone, aptly named, that I thought was...then told myself it couldn't be, was that Brendan Fraser?  Blinked and he was gone.  Why was he there, I forget.  This is one movie you could never spoil in the telling because who can remember what just happened?My synopsis of the movie: there were a lot of explosions.Even riddled with the occasional flashback (which served only to confuse matters), there wasn't much in the way of humanity involved here.  Tough talking, macho posturing (especially by THE Baroness, Sienna Miller), withering putdowns (the obligatory slur, "ladies!"), toy names (who would name their kid Heavy Duty or Snake Eyes!?), and deliriously impossible combat sequences that everyone seems to survive with barely a scratch (who thinks Storm Shadow won't be back?).By the time The Rise of Cobra had set up its sequel my brain was having spasms, begging them to stop the torture: I'LL TALK!  I'LL TELL YOU ANYTHING YOU WANT....No, it wasn't a keeper, and no, I won't be watching the sequel or the one that follows it.  I'd sooner stare at a sparkler for 2 hours.
summary: "Technically, G.I. Joes don't exist."  If only!

reviewText: "G.I. Joe" is a clandestine, multinational, special forces unit with the highest technology available and a mission to defend the world from any threat.  Our hero, Duke, is protecting a shipment of the most advanced warheads when his convoy is ambushed by an unknown unit with advanced weapons and superior information, led by a woman he knows.  The ambushers get away after G.I. Joe rescues the remnants of the convoy.  Duke and his teammate Ripcord sign on with G.I. Joe and go after the organization that ambushed them.First rate comic book fun.  Lots of explosions and gunfights, and larger than life heros.  What made it unexpectedly good were the backstories and histories of the Joe team members and their adversaries.  Duke and his ex-wife, the family history of the villain behind the ambush, the evil scientist behind the advanced warhead and others have a web of relationships that provide a depth that you don't normally expect in this sort of fluff.On the other hand, the laws of Newtonian physics were clearly suspended for the duration.Although it was a complete story, none of the key characters died, and the stage is set for sequel.  I'll be looking forward to it, especially to seeing where Lady J and Ripcord end up.Great fun with some unexpected layers!E. M. Van Court

reviewText: To complain that a summer blockbuster is derivative is like whining about the sugar in your candy; once you've tried it, you should know what to expect.  Yet "G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra" contains a significant number of "homages" even when considering the standards of its genre.In truth, it's not a bad movie.  "Rise of Cobra" contains a number of gratifying action sequences, and the special effects on the whole are quite good.  It's also fun for the grown man who enjoyed the toys of his youth to watch the story unfold and ask himself, for example, "Is that the Baroness?"  And every scene involving Storm Shadow and Snake Eyes (old or young) is edge-of-your-seat good stuff.  There is a lot to keep the casual fan involved.The problem is, many scenes trigger deja vu in a distracting way.  Take, for example, a shot of slo-mo backflips over projectile weapons in a narrow city street: "Transformers," anyone?  Or consider the targeting of the Eiffel Tower by a terrorist organization.  We saw that in "Team America: World Police," a much better movie in more than one way (here's a hint: it never takes itself too seriously).  The accelerator suits certainly made me think of "Ironman" on more than one occasion.  The trope of the friend who turns on you--because of a woman--seemed copied-and-pasted from "The Dark Knight."  And I won't go into the many parallels with the "X-Men" trilogy, as that might spoil a few plot twists, but this comparison too was inescapable.So I left the theater feeling a little disappointed.  Not because "Rise of Cobra" was bad, but because I felt I had seen it a time or two before, and recalled it being just a little bit better.
summary: Haven't I seen this movie before?

reviewText: If you need a movie that doesn't try to be anything other than what it is, that's also a pure action movie, then you've just described G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra perfectly. Coming from Director Steven Sommers, who after 'Van Helsing' stopped taking himself seriously, doesn't really take anything seriously in this movie. There is a plot, that tries to take itself seriously, but towards the middle of the movie I think it just gives up and throws in Cobra's story every once and a while. And yes, if you try to give the bad guys motivation, 9 times out of 10 it fails, and watching this film it's a 4 out of 4.Channing Tatum, that "cute" guy with the Army haircut takes on the burden of playing G.I. Joe, sure, it's technically an organization, but he's basically an action figure in this movie, and his acting attests to that. But even with all this, I did find his character somewhat interesting in that he's this super soldier, but no matter what he does he's a screw-up. He tries to help his friend, his face gets Vadarized. He tries to save the Eiffel Tower, it's partially intact when it topples over and kills a ton of people. If the filmmakers care about character development in the sequel, this feature to the character would be very interesting to expand on. The rest of the Joe team is pretty good, but a little unmemorable. Except in a bad way for Marlon Wayans, who stayed away from his brothers' crappy movies, but gets saddled with all these awful jokes. Also, even though Dennis Quaid is shown in all the trailers and is given high billing, he mails it in for all of the five minutes he's there.But wait, then there's Snake Eyes. Channing Tatum is the "star" of this film, but Snake Eyes is the most bad-a** dude here. First, he doesn't talk because he's taking a lifelong vow of silence, and he's an awesome fighter. Really, some of his sword-fighting sequences are some of the best I've seen in years. Even the child version of him is kicks butt. Snake Eyes looks cool, gets the job done, and is the film's breakout character.Action-wise, it's like a best-of summer action films. There's chases in vehicles, underwater, in the air, with swords, with guns, with fists & feet. Did I miss any? Basically if you ask what kind of action this film has, I say all the above. For the most part, all of it works, it's all pretty cool, and it never overstays its welcome. Also, at home Blu-Ray & an awesome home theater system will mean everything to this movie, and it increases the experience ten-fold. And yes, perhaps the film's best sequence, and one of the best action sequences I've seen in a while is the Paris chase with the accelerator suits. It's incredibly self-indulgent with slow motion, but I loved every minute of it.There are also two great unique elements to the movie I found enjoyable.1. The movies makes very heavy use of the flashback sequence to give the backstory for all the main characters, and while it does slow it down some because there's not really any action to them, I applaud the effort and I found them pretty engaging.2. Having seen a lot of these future technology weapons on the History Channel, it's pretty cool seeing the movie making heavy use of this advanced technology working the way it would really work, and not a Hollywood version of it. Somers says all the tech will be in use in 20 years, and I highly doubt it, but it's cool to see these futuristic weapons grounded in reality for once.Overall, I enjoyed the film quite a bit, the action-phile I am, and it's a great way to lose two hours. It never loses it's welcome, and it provides a lot of satisfactory bones thrown to the audience. It never takes itself seriously, as it shouldn't, and you shouldn't either, because you'll wind up disappointed. For the G.I. Joe fans, if you're a fans of 60s/70s Joe, it's in name only unless you count the scar on Channing Tatum. As for the 80s cartoon Joe fans, you'll most likely find yourself highly pleased since the movie takes most of its universe from the cartoon series.
summary: Put Me Down For An Accelerator Suit, Please!

reviewText: If the animated show was a part of your childhood and you wish to take a trip down nostalgia lane, then buy the animated set without hesitation . . . because this live action version of the series will disappoint you. Besides the action and stories and military technicalities of this show, I remember loving the interactions of all the different characters and the great chemistry between the friends and romantic couples like Flint and Lady Jay, Destro and the Baroness and especially, Scarlett and Duke. I can only guess that Hasbro has taken leave of its senses because it has recklessly allowed the makers of the film to pull a Bryan Singer and completely change the mythology of this original series. The action scenes were great, the CGI is state of the art, the music is good and the origin story on Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow was well done. But, TRAGICALLY, it appears that once they decided to cast Sienna Miller as the Baroness, they must have felt compelled to make her the star of the film which meant making her the female lead heroine opposite the male lead hero, Duke!!! Yes, ladies and gentlemen, the current released movie version of this wonderful series omits one of the major components of what made this series wonderful in the first place: the original, established love stories.In the original animated show, Destro is a burly, deep voiced, authorative, powerful character (easy to understand why the Baroness loves him)- more so than the Cobra Commander versus the movie where he is a stringy, funny looking, squeeky voiced old guy with a Scottish accent and a stalker-like attitude toward the Baroness!In the original series, the Baroness, herself, is a deliciously cool and conniving character integral to the workings of the COBRA organization versus the current film which actually starts really well then slams you into a twisted, distracting, boring and idiotic thread where the Baroness is made out to be an American under mind control by the little brother (Cobra Commander) she believed dead, caused by the guy she was engaged to - Duke.In the series, Scarlett is THE number one woman on the Joe Team and in Duke's heart. In the TERRIBLY written movie, Scarlett has a crush on - Ripcord.The sheer stupidity that Hollywood film makers keep engaging in time after time after time is mind blowing! If something is good, they always think they can make it better. If something is NOT broken, they ruin it!! Wether it's giving Lois Lane an illigitmate child and turning Superman into a stalker a la Mr. Bryan Singer, or introducing superlana and previously non-existant sidekick chloe to Smallville, or even dishing out millions of dollars to give Halle Berry the chance to show off her more-animal-than-human moronic and unattractive version of Catwoman, you can almost always count on those selfless movie people to do away with nice bits of childhood art appreciation and hand you the tripe concocted by their ginormously over-priced egos instead!The exception of changing mythos is Transformers. In the original series, there was no love story. What's more, I always thought it was funny how the Dad and son who befriend the Autobots were always wearing their yellow hard hats. In the two live action movies, for once, spielberg's team, actually improved on an already established storyline by adding a love story and digging deeper into the human/robot friendship. It is just plain SAD that G.I. Joe was not given better movie treatment because, again, there were already established love stories that would have been fun to see translated onto the big screen.I recommend you watch this film only when you don't feel like thinking too much and just want to be entertained with an all action and CGI flick. However, I highly reccomend the G.I. Joe animated sets. Buy them, enjoy them . . . because if you were a G.I. Joe fan in your childhood, this movie currently in theaters will bum you out.
summary: A Disappointment in Storyline but Succeeded in Action

reviewText: As with any typical comic book / cartoon turned movie project, character development takes a sideline because of the sheer number of characters in the film. Recent examples include Transformers and Spider Man. However, as someone that grew up with the GI Joe cartoons, action figures, vehicle toys, etc... I felt this movie was moderately acceptable.My biggest complaints are with how they changed re-imagined the story, and the cheezy CGI. Physics don't apply to any of the action sequences. Scarlett, while being smoking hot, "performs" feats in a motorcycle that break every law of physics to the point it was painful to watch. The accelerator suits were a nice touch, but the CGI didn't make them seem very probable even in the near future. I love Sci-Fi and mech suits, but I thought it would be a bit more palatable if the accelerator suits had jump jets / flight capability ala Apple Seed.The good parts are still aplenty. The Cobra/MARS fortress and the GI Joe base fall into the same category of "crazy, but apropos" concepts found in the original cartoon. The underwater weaponry also aligns with the laser-beams that they used in the cartoons.Overall, I give Rise of Cobra 3/5 stars and recommend it as a rental on the weekend. Grab some popcorn and just relax.
summary: As a GI Joe fan, this movie was OK

reviewText: BackgroundThe G.I. Joe trademark and franchise has its origins in the realm of toys. In 1964, Hasbro launched a line of realistic 12" action figures that represented various divisions of the military services. Later in 1982, a smaller line (3.75 inches) of these toys were introduced. With this line an entire storyline was also told. This story involved the battles between the G.I. Joe forces and the evil Cobra Command. It is from this storyline that this movie takes it queue.StorylineThe storyline is one that is closely knit around life long enemies, past lovers and good friends. At various points, there are flashbacks to fill in the missing pieces. The main article of contention are 4 warheads that contain a newly developed technology - Nanomites. These miniature robots and be programmed to eat metal and any other material as necessary, and can literally destroy anything in their path until they are deactivated.Action SequencesThere is plenty of action sequences throughout this film. There is a full set of high tech vehicles (air, land, underground and sea) to captivate your imagination. The sequence that I like the most is the street chase scene in Paris. I haven't seen such an intensely packed road sequence since the Matrix Reloaded. The guys in their body suits are simply fantastic!Another great fight sequence is the final one between Storm Shadow and Snake Eyes (Ray Park - who also acted as Dart Maul - Star Wars Episode I) - Excellent sword play!ConclusionGreat Action film, produced for the Action Man.

reviewText: I'm sorry I couldn't find anything at all to like about this film.  This has to be the absolute King of those blockbuster films that love to hurl all sorts of poorly edited CGI filled action sequences at the viewer and hope that no one will notice the complete lack of coherence, character development or plot.  Yep, this is WORSE than TRANSFORMERS 2, TERMINATOR 4, 2012 and all the rest of the overbudgeted underwhelming nonsense the studios love to crank out.  There just wasn't anything to enjoy here. I loved GI Joe as a kid but this film has no genuine relationship to the GI joe stuff I grew up with.  Thats fine if the film makers had bothered to change it into something thoughtful, interesting or entertaining.  They didn't.  It's just one gigantic incomprehensible action sequence after another and for me, that isn't enough to make a film worthwhile.

reviewText: I don't know what it is yet. I've tried to figure it out but so far nothing. I go into these types of movies knowing they could be stupid (Transformers 2) or disappointing (Watchmen). I'm not expecting much...I mean, if I want Oscar performances or something with meaning I'll got to an art house movie theater and catch something indie.Whatever the reason, this movie just took me along for the ride and kept me entertained the whole way. Maybe it's the great action throughout...maybe it's the awesome marital arts between Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow...maybe it's the toned down hotness of Scarlett and the Baroness (they tease with their beauty, no need for anything excessive here). The movie grabs you with early action and keeps going. The story unfolds with tossed in highlights of the pasts of a handful of the characters so you can understand what's going on but doesn't waste any more time than is necessary. Looking for feelings and emotion? The touchy-feelly aisle is over there. This movie's just here to entertain and keep you guessing in places.Meanwhile the tech is great even if some of it is infeasible. But even that...I'm a military junkie so when things get out of hand, it's hard not to notice...here, I didn't mind it (okay, it was bugging me a bit at the end with the jet but that's beside the point).The movie's a fun ride and gets you there without wasting too much time on boring scenes the director wanted in there for some unknown reason. The plot is actually not bad considering but it's irrelevant in the end. This is about GI Joe vs Cobra (or what will become Cobra) and you're here to have fun.My only complaint about this (I got both Blu-Ray and standard DVD versions, by the way so this applies to both--what can I do, we don't have Blu-Ray in the living room) is how they started packaging these movies. It used to be that when you saw "2 Disk Set + Digital Copy" that meant you got 2 Disks of content and a digital copy on one of the disks or on a separate disk. Now, they're still calling it a 2-disk set but the second disk has all of 2, count them, 2 special features (a making of and a sfx doc). Especially with Blu-Ray...the whole idea is the disks include more storage space so you can fit the HD version but also fit a lot of other content.To me, a film this big deserves the extra content and that needs to include a lot more than two featurettes. Honestly, let me download the digital copy or something and give me more like gag reels, docs on other parts of the behind the scenes stuff. Or else call it a 1 Disk + Digital Copy set and call it a day. Need another disk for the digital copy? Fine, charge me the extra $0.50 it costs to add the disk (including shipping!) and put it in there on a separate disk.This is like what food retailers do with the reduced size packaging that "looks" like it hasn't changed but is thinner, taller-but-narrower, or some other deceptive format. It's obvious greed and is not appreciated, despite the price of the Blu-Ray. If it wasn't for that, I'd give this sucker a five-star rating (rare for me). If you haven't seen it and like solid action, grab this in either format.
summary: I can't help it...I loved this movie

reviewText: Remember this cartoon? I remember the original G.I. Joe - the 12" doll in the fatigues. Madison Ave. kept after the kid market with military themed toys in the 80's and 90's with a re-vamped, technologically advanced Joe(s) - including a silent, black clad ninja. Now we have the big-budget, action-packed summer movie about these characters. Is it any good?Surprise, G.I. Joe is a good summer movie. I expected to see some villian bursting into a room crowded with Joes (all wearing different uniforms, one even wearing a parrot on his shoulder), firing a machine gun while somebody yells "DUCK!"; which results in no one getting hurt. That does'nt happen in this movie - its actually very violent, although you don't see too much blood. The movie also displays some very cool weapons and ships.Well worth one's time.
summary: Better Than A Toy Commercial Ought To Be..

reviewText: This movie takes whatever fond childhood memory I've had of G.I. Joe and gives it a mean hurtful wedgie. I went to see this one months ago and, based on that crapalicious trailer (ya know, the one with the armored suits), I wasn't expecting to be overwhelmed. Or even whelmed. This movie doesn't aim too high, and so it hits its target audience. G.I. JOE: THE RISE OF COBRA is what it is - a big budget summertime popcorn flick in which the big dogs figured that as long as it's slick and peopled with cool and beautiful actors and chock full of dazzling and eardrum-shattering effects, then that'll do for the sheep. The critics showered it with hate. And, sheepishly, I wasn't as turned off as I maybe should've been. I'm giving it a generous 3 stars out of 5, thanks to the inner kid in me which may be not cool with what's been done here but, on the other hand, is just grateful that G.I. Joe finally made it to the big screen as a live action picture.Odds are, any movie featuring a Wayans brother instantly surrenders busloads of credibility. This one lost a few more points with me once Marlon Wayons started mugging for the camera. I give the writers credit for trying to come up with a story from the ground level up, this by having Duke and Ripcord introduced as fresh recruits to this elite military team. This gives us two point-of-view characters to identify with. There's a lot of stuff going on. The movie depends on the audiences' childhood familiarity with the characters to pull them thru all the hectic.The plot is big and bloated, the dialogue is dumbed down, the action sequences a showcase for big budget excesses. What's missing is heart and, okay, a solid script and enough actors who can sell the storyline. It's a bit damning that, for me, the two most absorbing characters happen to be the black ninja with the vow of silence and the vampy bespectacled villainess. I guess, for the lead, they tried to find a stud who was hip and smoove and relatable, and Tatum Channing must've fit the bill. But I feel that he was miscast as Duke, that he lacks the necessary acting chops and that sense of solidity and resolve, despite all claims from his buddy Wayans that "Duke wasn't born, he was government-issued." Tatum Channing sleepwalks thru this one, and one wonders what Sam Worthington would've done with this role (it was offered to Worthington but dude had to do AVATAR). And, as for Marlon Wayans, well, there he is, standing there just being a Wayans. We really could've done with more of Dennis Quaid's General Hawk. Good thing, then, that the guy is signed on for two sequels.The story is set somewhen "in the not too distant future," which then allows for some pretty impressive future tech from both the good guys and the bad. The Joes, for example, flaunt a coat enabling extreme camouflage and clunky one-man armors called Delta 6 Accelerator Suits (the unconvincing demonstration of which seriously cheesed me off). The McGuffin of the movie are frightfully corrosive nanomites which can dissolve metal in mere moments. This frightening weapon is what one formidable terrorist organization holds over the free world. Unless General Hawk's special unit can save the day. And, even then, the bad guys are tricky enough and far-thinking enough that Duke and company can't possibly foil each of their contingency plans. So, sequel, anyone?Some credit goes to the movie for trying to add detail to its characters' backstories. Same credit is then snatched away for the numbing and excessive flashbacks. There's too much dawdling, also, in some scenes early on in which the bad guys talk on and on about their big nefarious scheme. But two things, more than anything else, bugged the heck out of me: a) Being a Snake Eyes fan, I wasn't cool with Scarlett and Ripcord doing the flirty flirty, and b) Snake Eyes' mask has friggin' lips! What the --? Speaking of flirting, Duke and the Baroness having a past history is new to me, not that I minded it all that much, and their relationship turns out to be pretty key to the story. But I thought it's always been "Destro and the Baroness practicing the clarinet" (and if you don't get that reference, check out the Funny or Die website for the awesome Ballad of G.I. Joe video clip).The fighty fights to watch out for are the grudge matches between Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow. There's also a nice bit between Scarlett and the Baroness, and I understand that both the very fine actresses (Rachel Nichols, Sienna Miller) actually suffered injuries while filming the scene. The rest of the action sequences are slick and big and must have cost a ton, but I just couldn't get into them. Just something so soulless and by-the-numbers to them, I think. And the bits with the exterior shots of the Pit (the G.I. Joe headquarters) somewhere in the Egyptian desert? Look very unconvincing.The actors playing the baddies carry the actors playing the heroes. There's something gleeful in how Christopher Eccleston, Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Byung-hun Lee, Sienna Miller (yes, Sienna Miller), and Arnold Vosloo go about fleshing out their villainous parts. Gordon-Levitt gets a chance to chew the scenery a bit as the kookybag who would eventually become the Cobra Commander. In this movie, the Terrordrome is still but a gleam in his rat crazy eyes.G.I. JOE: THE RISE OF COBRA, at least, isn't as bad as TRANSFORMERS: REVENGE OF THE FALLEN. But, y'know, I wouldn't have minded at all if they'd just taken the soldiers from the TRANSFORMERS flicks and revamped them into the Joes. Tyrese Gibson comes off as a more convincing and gritty elite commando than Marlon Wayans.I do like the off-handed way the iconic phrases were worked in ("real American heroes," "Knowing is half the battle," etc.). And despite Tatum Channing's weak interpretation, Duke remains my favorite Joe (And then Snake Eyes).Basically, if you were turned off by that trailer with the armor suits, then think of the film as one big extrapolation of that discontent. I'm glad G.I. Joe finally made it as a live action film, but damn...
summary: ...rise of Cobra, collapse of franchise? Probably not...

reviewText: The concept of someone rating this movie a 5 star puts the entire validity of the Amazon review system in question.The only reason, and I mean the ONLY reason to watch this movie is because you fast forward to the parts with attractive people (volume off is best) or because you want to be made physically uncomfortable.The original source material (the 80s comics) had a number of intriguing story lines that could have been followed to result in a very watchable, very interesting plot line. But I think that all the creators of this movie chose to study about the source material was the pop culture references to Joe printed on t-shirts. Even when they properly used the cultural references (half the battle is knowing) they didn't just make a passing reference to it, they pounded you over the head with it, making it an ongoing dialogue focus. It's like the comedian who nails a subtle punchline then just. keeps. talking.Every second that ticked by in this movie was another click down the path of disgusting writing, acting, and over the top pointless special effects.If you were a fan of GI Joe, or like great action movies, or don't enjoy good actors being made to look like middle school drama dropouts, skip this movie. And if you're thinking about buying it before watching it, you're clinically insane.
summary: GI Joe: The ruin of a franchise

reviewText: Remember how Michael Bay and Shia LaBarf dropped a steaming deuce on your childhood memories of Transformers?  Well, the crew responsible for the miasma lingering around this rendition of GI Joe have upped the ante.Starting off with the bad, this is a collection of some of the worst acting and casting in movie history.  Siena Miller and Rachel Nichols look gorgeous the entire movie, but their more serious roles were on runways and in Dumb and Dumberer, respectively.  Channing "Pinocchio" Tatum reprises his emotionless military figure from Stop-Loss while perfecting acting without facial expressions of voice inflection that he flawlessly pulled off in Dear John.  Others like Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje are all brought down by the rest.  To make matters worse, the guy playing Snake Eyes doesn't have any lines and he's the best actor.  The biggest travesty, however, is that Dennis Quaid was relegated to horribly predictable one-liners that serve no purpose other than to echo the mid-movie comments made by viewers who have figured out every storyline twist and turn eons before they occur.  His part may as well have been a holographic face in the top-right corner of the screen with a robotic voiceover.  Speaking of voiceovers, did I mention how horrible Tatum is?  My goodness, I feel like I just divided by zero, because the impossible has happened: there is an actor in Hollywood worse than Keanu Reeves.The flaws and plot-holes are so numerous they are not worth mentioning, but would it kill someone to remake a movie and stick even remotely close to the original storyline that everyone already loved?  The nonsensical side stories with Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow didn't happen; there was no engagement between Duke and Baroness - and definitely wasn't a connection between Scarlett and Ripcord.  And what they did with Cobra Commander - making him a scientist with secretive ties to GI Joe members - is absolutely ridiculous.  None of these plot add-ons resonate with new viewers, much less attract longtime fans.As for the plot-holes, pick your favorites; they are too numerous to mention.  The overabundance of extras (e.g. nanotechnology, unnecessary background, underwater jets, strange energy rays, acceleration suits, multi-billion dollar facilities under the polar ice caps and the Egyptian deserts, etc.) is at times interesting and at others maddening.  It's just too much to be coherent.  The inclusion of multi-national forces in an organization that is supposed to be American (Hello! A real American hero...) is a slap in the face to the GI Joe canon.  Seeing soldier chums Duke (Tatum) and Ripcord (Wayans) wiggle their way into this ultra-secretive and best-of-the-best military commando unit because, you know, they really want to, is just too much to bear.If you're into this for the action and special effects (read: more CGI than Toy Story), and you loved the Transformer movies, then I suppose you'll like it.  I'd rather have the shade of gray that provides a bit more story, significantly better dialogue, and actors who can't be easily replaced by mannequins.  Overall it's just a little bit of good (i.e. Miller and Nichols in form-fitting, cleavage-producing outfits, and Snake Eyes' fight scenes) in a pile of garbage (i.e. acting, casting, CGI, plot, directing).Jason Elin
summary: Digesting eye candy in a bowl of raw sewage
