reviewText: I'm one of the rare 30something guys that didn't really play with GI Joes or watch the cartoon, although I liked the comics (Marvel and Devils' Due versions), which had a more mature, complicated presentation of GI Joe, so I came into the movie without a strong childhood connection.  I'll split my review into Plot, Characters/Acting, and Visuals/Action.-Plot: First off, I could not help but notice how much of the plot was pulled from the Devils Due GI Joe comics; the nanomites and Destro's history are directly from it, which I liked because it added some extra depth. This is not a thoughtful, Dark Knight-esque movie, but a summer action film.  Despite that, the plot had some great twists and turns; character histories were also especially good. I liked the Duke/Baroness/Destro/"Doctor" connections, and the Snake-Eyes/Storm Shadow history was well presented.  What was best though, was the presentation of Cobra. these are not the incompetents from the cartoon, they are brilliant, clever, and vicious.  They actually destroyed the Eiffel Tower for crying out loud!  Most action flick villains aren't that accomplished, so props to them for being successful.  There's also the very nice setup for the sequel that actually got me clapping. The only thing I did not like was confusion about who the Doctor was; I kept confusing him with Mindbender.  Sometimes it seems they tried to stuff too much into the film, but overall it didn't drag.-Characters/Acting: Getting some good actors helped out with this; Sienna Miller as the Baroness made the movie; she may not have had the accent, but the icy viciousness was there in spades, and makes glasses sexy.  I also liked Arnold Vosloo as Zartan, but he didn't get anywhere near enough screen time; hopefully that will change for the next movie.  The ninjas were both perfect.  As for Duke, I agree with others that he was pretty flat.  However, Duke was always the "good guy" who didn't really have a personality in the comics, so I partly think Tatum had nothing to work with.  The "Doctor" was on the other extreme; the Commander was always like that, but I felt it was done in a way that detracted, so the interactions between Duke and the Doctor were tough to take.  There were some good lines too; "Duke wasn't born, he was government issued!".-Visuals/Action: Very nice.  The CGI looked pretty good, and the explosions were aweseome; the car chase through Paris was a particularly good one, especially the part with the train.  Based on that scene alone, you know chars definitely get hurt in this movie!  The nanomites were pretty good.  Fight scenes were great, although I felt the Storm Shadow/Snake-Eyes fights should have been better and longer; I actually liked the fight between the kid versions of them better; no holds barred there!  The girlfight between Scarlett and the Baroness should go into the Top 5 Best Girlfights of all time, and really shows off how the female chars are some of the most dangerous chars in the movie.To conclude, GI Joe was an excellent action flick that contained some good plot (better than Transformers 2 anyway), did great homage/respect for  the established characters, and some very nice setups.  It's not thoughtful or brilliant, but does make for a good time.

reviewText: What I like about this movie is that everyone at least tries hard and that the movie is some fun. While the script is decent and tries as much as possible to explain why this person or that person are holding a grudge with each other through many flashbacks. The movie is better than you'd expect and it at least is less disappointing than some of the other movies to be released this summer. It delivers more than the summer movies that I expected to be a lot better than they were.It has a very big cast and Stephen Sommers (The Mummy, Van Helsing) does a fine job giving everyone a good amount of screen time. He gets trash talked about him, but he's honestly better than Michael Bay and McG are at least. One problem I had was Joseph Gordon Levitt (Brick,The Lookout) being cast against type as Cobra Commander. It worked for Heath Ledger as the Joker, but doesn't work here. He's a very talented actor and tries hard to be sinister and it does almost work but I also had a hard time trying not to laugh. I just don't see why he has been cast in villains roles of late.But the best casting was of Ray Park (X-Men, Sleepy Hollow) as Snake Eyes. He was perfectly cast in the role and the movie is it's most fun when he's on screen. The movie could have been a lot worse, someone only yelled "Yo Joe!" once and none of the bad guys ever yelled "COBRA!!!". Still, it would have been better if Marlon Wayans took a vow of silence like Snake Eyes.

reviewText: Going into this movie I honestly thought it was going to be terrible move, maybe 1 star or worse, but I was pleasantly surprised that it wasn't as bad as I thought it would be. That being said I wouldn't pay to see it in the theater I'd wait till it comes out on DVD and rent it.The story was bad and had major plot holes or didn't make any sense, but what can you expect from a Stephen Sommers movie(As you can tell I really don't like the his directing/writing).The acting was decent with Dennis Quaid(General Hawk), Christopher Eccleston(Destro). He's also good in Doctor Who. Byung-hun Lee(Storm Shadow) and Ray Park(Snake Eyes). Though Sommers and the rest of the writers destroyed their great stories from they had from the cartoon and comics. As for everyone else from Channing Tatum to Marlon Wayans pretty much sucked.Action/Special Effects I thought were the best part of the film. The high not was the battle in Paris which was great. The other action scenes were visual good but weren't well executed especially the underwater one.Now for my tangent on the so call director Stephen Sommers. Back to my first question. Can Stephen Sommers direct, and the overwhelming evidence says NO!Lets look at the list of films he has directed.Deep Rising, The Mummy, The Mummy Returns, Van Helsing, and GI Joe. The only film that I though was above mediocre was The Mummy which I gave 3 1/2 stars. The rest were Mediocre to terrible.Now lets look at all the things he's written/screenplay.Deep Rising, The Mummy, The Mummy Returns, The Scorpion King, Van Helsing, and G.I. Joe. Again the only really decent film was The Mummy. Is he the worst director/writer out there of course not but he is really bad.Now if this movie manages to make enough money to garner a sequel. Which I truly think is in question. Here are a few things their going to need to do to bring me back.1. Get rid of Stephen Sommers. There are a lot better directors than him.2. Get rid of Channing Tatum and Marlon Wayans. They were two of the worst actors in this film.3. Make the third film better. I'd say less is more. You don't have to have these over the top actions scenes to have make entertaining movie. Also add move depth to the characters like Snake Eyes, Scarlet and Destro. Last thing add more drama and suspense.If the producers can do the majority of this I'd be on board for another film other wise this potential franchise is done.

reviewText: I initially had difficulty in rating this film, as there is much to be annoyed with it.At the top of the list are the obvious PC alterations to the GI Joe brand.*GI Joe is an AMERICAN special forces unit, but the film changes that to some UN force so as not to offend the sensibilities of the international market. (Yet, somehow movies about CIA operatives and the like are still successful, without having to change the CIA into Interpol.)* Cobra Commander's lame mask, because they were afraid that a hood would be offensive because it resembles a KKK hood. Cobra Commander is the TERRORIST leader! Who were they afraid of offending by making the terrorist look like a klansman? The KKK, or terrorists? Who else, after all, would be offended?* Channing Tatum's attitude (behind the scenes) of initially not wanting to do the movie so as not to glorify the military/war, yet changing his mind when it showed that the script was more akin to a superhero movie. Of course, the movie still had a high body count with a lot of bystanders getting injured/killed. Hey Channing, how many people do you think said, "I'd love to see that kind of action," after seeing something like "We Were Soldiers"? It's actually movies like this that glorify violence and make it look "fun".* The black guy portraying Ripcord, a white character. Why not have a black guy portray Stalker, one of the coolest of the original Joes? Because the name "Stalker" might offend.Then there were the poor ideas.* Snake-Eyes in a rubber suit with a mask with lips. What were they thinking?!?! Just put him in a regular, black colored uniform. Remove the lips. He looked like an oversized, alien muppet. And a vow of silence is why he can't speak? Why not leave the original story, that all others have used? He wears the mask and does not talk because he was disfigured in some explosion that damaged his vocal cords as well. (I mean, who is going to admit someone into an elite military force who refuses to talk?)* The accelerator suits. If they were just armored suits they would have been fine (or if used by Cobra), but making them run as fast as a car? That would rip your body apart if you had some outside force moving your limbs about that fast. (And why did the two rookies get these, while the experienced members of the team sit in the van?)So why the four stars?Well I have to admit, despite the above flaws, I did enjoy the movie.It works very well as a generic action/sci-fi movie and the plot (other than the PC changes) was actually well thought out. The bad guys actually had a clever plan and the twist was that it actually worked, despite the Commander ending up in custody at the end.So even though there are several aspects about this movie that make me, as a GIJoe fan, cringe (another being the Duke, Baroness, Destro love triangle), I am not such an absolute purist that it kept me from enjoying a fun, reasonably well acted (given what it is), and clever action flick.If you are one of the GI Joe fans that has refused to see this up till now, I would recommend taking a chance on it. If you are one of those action movie fans that has taken a pass becuase its "GI Joe", I say the same thing.

reviewText: Director Stephen Sommers has had box office hits, "The Mummy", "The Mummy Returns" and even the poorly written "Van Hellsing". All his films had a certain zing and lots of humor, which sometimes worked like in "The Mummy" but other times it seemed forced rather than breezy.Now he brings the G.I. Joe franchise to the big screen and despite my early fears turned out to be the perfect blend of action, humor, nostalgia and of course bad acting. The film involves a group of bad guys working for an arms dealer named McCullen (Christopher Eccelston, "The Others") and Cobra (Joseph Gordon-Levitt, T.V.'s "Third Rock From The Sun" and "500 Days of Summer") trying to capture 4 warheads with nano-technology that can destroy any metal objects it comes into contact with.The good guys of course are a covert group named G.I. Joe, lead by General Hawk (Dennis Quiad, "The Rookie"). He recruits two soldiers Duke (Channing Tatum, "Fast and The Furious: Tokyo Drift") and Ripcord (Marlon Wayans, "The Scary Movie" franchise) who were on a covert mission to deliver the warheads when Cobra soldiers intercepted and captured em.There's a bit of a story here beyond that but not much, McCullen designed the warheads and wants to use them to control the world. There's also a side sotry with Duke and Ana aka The Baroness (Sienna Miller, "Casanova" and "Stardust"), they were to be married but certain events caused their relationship to fall apart.There's also a character called Snake Eyes, a fully costumed master swordsman (Ray Park, Darth Maul in "The Phantom Menace") who has a score to settle with Storm Shadow (Byung-hun Lee). Other cool characters include Zartan (Arnold Vosloo, "The Mummy" and "The Mummy Returns") and Scarlett (Rachel Nichols, "The Amityville Horror"). Even Jonathan Pryce makes an appearance as the President of the U.S.There are problems like the shear unbelievable stunts, some of the writing goes beyond cheesy and is just bad and honestly Tatum is one of the most wooden actors besides Josh Harnett and Keanu Reeves.The good points are the action and pacing are both well done, the humor is dead on most of the time and for the guys (and statistically some of the girls) Miller and Nichols look beyond fantastic. They did get a lot of the nostalgia of the old cartoon, like the laser effects and sounds and the overall good ol' American come to the rescue aspect. *** out of 4 stars

reviewText: It's not that I don't accept summer blockbusters for what they are; the industry would be foolish to deny audiences these enjoyable dollops of mental junk food during our summer months.That said, this summer has certainly met its quota for the year, with Joe being just short of an excessive addition.  Unable to distinguish itself from other cinematic behemoths of the past few months - aside, perhaps, from its admirable ability to never take itself seriously - Sommers' tireless action romp feels stale this late in the game.The film consistently teeters on the edge of self-conscious family fun and uninspired, shallow flash that cant compensate for being late to the blockbuster party.That said, it's truly difficult to criticize Joe too much in the wake of a certain other summer juggernaut that used similar elements of enticement to lure audiences in, only to make them suffer through worthless side stories and slapstick comedy (I'm throwing tomatoes at YOU, Mr. Bay).  Here's two hours of film that knows what it is, and isn't afraid to work with what its got to the fullest extent.The acting, like the special effects, are merely satisfactory, with even Wayans looking surprisingly comfortable in a significant role.  While this is nothing to throw on the tag line, rest assured that everyone really does pull their weight in GI Joe.Still, there's certainly an air of obsolescence to Joe that is ultimately its biggest issue.  Aside from fleeting moments of nostalgia that only a handful of audiences will experience, this is a movie that just has no real identity.

reviewText: G.I. Joe: The Rise of the Cobra: 7 out of 10: I think I may have liked this movie less had I not recently sat through the two and a half hour opus that is Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen. GI Joe is like Transformers with a coherent plot and a half an hour of stupid removed. (Notice I said half an hour not all.)First, let us get the ugly out of the way. GI Joe is no longer 'A Real American Hero' instead it is a group of foreigners led by Dennis Quaid and answerable to well nobody as far as I can tell. While I understand the change from a cowardly international marketing point of view, it really is a sad state of affairs. However, since all the real heroes turn out to be Americans after all and the bad guys are mostly foreigners from despot countries like Scotland and Japan, it is less jarring of a change than one would suppose.If you can get past the fact the GI Joe Corps is a secret international army (no doubt enforcing the upcoming one world order), has weapons more advanced than the US troops and yet is still inexplicably called GI JOE. (I had assumed at some point Dennis Quaid would declare it is a lame acronym such as Global Initiative something something Expedition alas to his credit he does not.) You still have to deal with some of the casting choices.While I am not overly familiar with the GI Joe mythos, I did see a major flaw on the Joe side. Channing Tatum simply does not look or act like Duke. Now Duke is the main character and everyman of the Joes. If you are familiar with the Duke Nukem videogame, think that guy with less one-liners and titty bar visits. Channing simply does not have the charisma or presence to pull of the character and the script does not give him much help.The other character the script torpedoes is The Baroness. She is the bad girl of the GI Joe universe and is played brilliantly by Sienna Miller (It really helps to hire great actors for these roles sometimes). The storyline unfortunately softens the Baroness to the point that by the end Duke is carrying her out of the exploding bad guys headquarters in his arms. (The bad guys lose. I hope that is not a spoiler in a movie called G.I. Joe)The other main characters are well represented. Marlon Wayans plays the black comic relief in the form of Ripcord (Dukes buddy). Normally I am aghast at the ethnic comic relief but Wayans pulls it off with aplomb. Rachel Nichols might seem a strange choice to play a smart woman, but she certainly looks the part and the whole Scarlett is an intellectual meme has clearly been toned down. She and Wayans have a romance that while safe for the kids may make adults in the audience dislocate their ciliary muscle.Rounding out the cast is a bunch of foreigners, Dennis Quaid, Jonathan Pryce as the President and an uncredited Brendan Fraser.The movie has a videogame feel and I mean that in the most complementary way. The weapons are out of a Sci-fi shooter. The Joes wear suits cribbed directly from the videogame Crackdown (Complete with the same powers); the very well shot action sequence in Paris will be quite familiar to any old school players of Twisted Metal 2.The finale is right out of any Roger Moore James Bond film. This is old school fun action, well shot, with a plot a seven year old could follow. There is some back-story and attempts at depth, but needless to say it is perfectly safe to turn your brain off for a few hours and enjoy the show.The plot is as follows. Bad guys steal evil weapon (Nanobite missiles). Good Guys get weapons back. Bad guys invade good guys headquarters killing cute blond and stealing missiles, Bad guys use missiles on unimportant foreign city (Paris) to show they mean business. Good Guys have their badges take away and are ordered to report to base. Good guys go to bad guys base instead. Good guys destroy bad guys underwater Arctic base by blowing up the icecap causing the underwater base to be crushed by the falling ice... hold on... falling ice????Yes, apparently in the GI Joe universe the concept that ice floats is just another unproven liberal egghead theory like evolution or the female orgasm. I guess that is what happens when you have a redheaded bimbo play your science officer. (Moreover, do not get me started on the chasing ballistic missiles with an airplane part.)The stupid is strong in this one... but so is the fun.
summary: G.I. Joe: The Rise of the Cobra...  Thinking is Half the Battle.

reviewText: Due to the great success from parlaying their Transformers toy line and various animated series' into box office gold, it was only a matter of time before toymaker Hasbro decided to try their luck with yet another of their long-standing toy brands, namely G.I. Joe. However, unlike the overwhelming sense of excitement I had when I saw the various trailers for both of the "Transformers" films, not to mention the actual films themselves; those heralding the forthcoming release of "G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra" were severely underwhelming to say the least. Despite a low amount of interest in the movie, I did finally get around to seeing it recently. Not surprisingly, much like my reaction to the film's trailers which were steeped in great disappointment; the actual experience of the movie itself was nothing short of an utter disaster, just on a much bigger scale than even I had anticipated."G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra" is essentially summed up by the title. Basically, an evil organization known as Cobra is attempting to become one of the deadliest terrorist cells on the planet. After a dangerous new weapon falls into Cobra's hands the world has only one hope for survival...G.I. Joe. A powerful covert military group, G.I. Joe is comprised of the very best operatives this world has ever seen, and when all else fails, they don't.Well, whenever a movie is this unabashedly bad the number of complaints that one can level against it can be quite staggering. Don't worry, I'll do my best to not bore you by listing every single one of them, but I will touch upon numerous problems along the way. So, the best thing to do is to just start at the backbone for the movie's failures... the story.The screenplay from writers Stuart Beattie ("30 Days of Night") and David Elliot & Paul Lovett ("Four Brothers"), all of whom have written far better films than this one, goes wrong in almost every way imaginable. Since the troubled areas for this movie's story are virtually all-encompassing, one could easily surmise that the writers never wanted to pen the movie in the first place. To be honest, if someone did have that thought (which I did), I don't honestly believe you would be that far from the truth.For a movie based on a continually successful toy line and an animated series that shaped many a child of the 80's, I was extremely disappointed in the paint by numbers approach the story took. The entire film felt like the writers were simply ticking off items on a checklist; for example, working in numerous classic lines of dialogue from the animated series (which sound extremely cheesy nowadays)... check, vehicles... check, iconic characters... check, and borrowing ideas from movies ten times better than this one... check. The problem with this approach is that none of it ever gelled in a natural fashion; instead, it all felt shoe-horned into the story to meet some sort of quota of G.I. Joe references and affiliations. Honestly, if more time had been spent on polishing up the dialogue, building up character development, and creating an actually interesting plot, then perhaps "G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra" could have been an entertaining movie, or at least had the potential to be one.The cast for this film was sub-par at best, which is sad when you realize that it was comprised of several very talented actors and actresses. Together this assemblage of assorted talents should have been able to offer up something better than what was put up on the screen, regardless of the irredeemable script. However, the majority of the cast members' performances felt stilted and uninspired, which by no means elevated the movie's already low entertainment value.Then there's the fact that I found myself surprised by certain actors' presence in a movie so obviously inferior to some of their previous films. For those that are curious, the cast members I was most disappointed in were Joseph Gordon-Levitt (who has proven himself to be quite the talented actor with intensely dramatic roles in films such as "The Lookout"), Dennis Quaid (who apparently was in dire need of a paycheck is my guess), and Channing Tatum (whose role in "A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints" earned him critical notice at Sundance Film Festival). These three actors, and a few others I didn't mention, all should have known better than to sign on to this movie. To make matters worse, most of the cast members, including the aforementioned, have signed for sequels, so they are stuck for the foreseeable future in what looks to be a horribly ill-conceived franchise.On the other hand, some of the other cast members I wasn't as disappointed in, for various reasons. Comedian and actor Marlon Wayans ("Scary Movie") does his level best to provide as many comedic moments in the movie as humanly possible, most likely in some doomed attempt to distract from the idiocy occurring everywhere else in the film. The problems with Marlon's character of Ripcord were numerous, but a couple of them would be the fact that his humor fell flat almost 90% of the time and the only real similarity this incarnation shares with his animated counterpart is the fact that he's an accomplished pilot. The reason Marlon didn't disappoint me was because I had no real expectations for him. I mean, consider his body of work, there's not much there to really be proud of, in my opinion.As for the actresses in the film, Sienna Miller ("Stardust") and Rachel Nichols ("Star Trek") added very little to the story other than the obvious eye candy for the predominantly male audience. I can say this about the two female leads, while their performances weren't impressive, they did excel in the aforementioned area that their presence was geared towards from the get-go. So at least in that respect, they did not disappoint either.Lastly, Ray Park's character of Snake Eyes was the sole member of the cast of characters that I was actually intrigued by. What makes this kind of humorous to me is the fact that he is never given any lines to speak; which is probably what allowed him to remain interesting. I almost feel sorry for Ray Park, because yet again his prowess with weapons and martial arts are the only reasons he was even included in the cast (other examples of this would be "Star Wars - Episode I: The Phantom Menace" and "Sleepy Hollow"). If this were the silent era of films the man could be one of the biggest stars in Hollywood rather than a glorified stuntman. You know, if the acting gigs ever dry up, perhaps he should consider becoming a mime. Then if someone didn't pay enough attention to him he could beat the snot out of them. Seems like a plausible scenario to me.Even though my expectations for this film were low from the very beginning, I thought that at least the movie's visual effects would stand some chance of impressing me. My belief that because the film was being directed by Stephen Sommers ("The Mummy"), that the movie's effects would be solid throughout was completely misplaced. I knew that from the previews a few of the scenes looked a little on the weaker side, but I gave them the benefit of the doubt on the off-chance that perhaps these were early cuts of the scenes that hadn't been fully finished at the time. However, shortly into my viewing of this movie I became well aware that much like the rest of the experience; the CGI would also prove to be an area of extreme weakness.The film utilized multiple effects houses, as is often the case with big budget blockbusters, so pinpointing one effects house as the source of the film's visual shortcomings is difficult. However, from what I can gather, it does appear that Digital Domain has been tagged as being responsible for the lion's share of the work in the film. That being the case, I feel it's only fair for me to hold them accountable for the majority of the abhorrently bad visual effects.What makes this failure on the part of Digital Domain even more shocking, in my mind, is the fact that their body of work has been downright stunning in past films. For example, they took part in some of the recent summer blockbusters; such as "Star Trek" and "Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen". So, my question Digital Domain is this, "What went so horribly wrong with your work on this film?" One visual effects trouble-spot was whenever CGI stunt doubles were being used. The lack of weight in their movements made them stand out like a sore thumb, and left me frustrated with just how unrealistic they appeared. Other problematic areas would be most of the shots involving various G.I. Joe or Cobra vehicles in action or completely CGI created set pieces that lacked any sense of realism. What this all boils down to is that almost every single visual effects shot in this film looked shoddy, and in my opinion there is just no excuse for this to be allowed given the capabilities we see on display in movies these days.So, what did I take away from this experience? Not a whole lot, aside from a newfound understanding of just how ridiculous some of those classic lines from the animated series really were or that the name G.I. Joe makes me laugh due to how comical it sounds. But seriously, this movie is a poor excuse for a summer blockbuster, and the fact that it can't even qualify as a guilty pleasure speaks volumes to just how horrible this movie is."G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra" is rated PG-13 for violence and language.
summary: This Movie is Terrible, and Knowing is Half the Battle...

reviewText: I have to start this review by saying I was a huge GI Joe fan growing up, first the cartoon and later the comic. So any change to the series I remember so fondly is tough. They had to run a fine line with this movie, appeal to those who loved and know GI Joe, while appealing to those who just wanted to see a good movie. I think the biggest problem I had with Rise of the Cobra is they tried to do too much with it. It is a fine line to create a movie based on a much loved and nostalgic comic/cartoon and do it in a modern way. I am all for updating and even a change in continuity if it helps the series and over all story, but I didn't get that from Rise of the Cobra. What I saw was a poor story, over acting, under acting and so much scene chewing it made me hungry and I had to make a trip to the lobby. The biggest issue is they took away so much of what made GI Joe unique. Forced multiculturalness, drastic changes to beloved characters, and the inability to tell if they wanted to make an action movie or a comedy. They had good actors and a lot of money to make this, with a better story and better direction this could have been great. If you haven't seen it yet I'd say to pass and if you really want to see an updated and adult version of GI Joe, then the animated GI Joe Resolute does the job so much better than this mess. Too bad really, I wanted nothing more than to write a review about how awesome this movie was, but it just isn't very good.

reviewText: I absolutely loved this movie and saw it twice when it was out in theaters.  While action-packed to the hilt there is an extremely well-done story and character development.It's true the screenplay doesn't follow the '80s cartoon (which I watched back in the day) nor the comic books (which I haven't read). It doesn't diminish it.As to the actual movie, the premise is simple enough.  There's a rising terrorist organization which has created a highly volatile weapon.  It doesn't care who it sells too...as long as it profits.  Or...so it seems.  There's a secret organization called G.I. JOE...a group made of the best operatives across the globe who seeks to thwart them from throwing the world into chaos. To say more regarding the characters and the roles they play on all this would be spoiling a bit of the film.I can, however, say that yes....one of the characters does indeed say the classicline:  "And knowing is half the battle"  even if in this case it's best to see the film for yourself.

reviewText: My wife and I recently made plans to go check out a movie with another couple.  When differences arose on which movie we were to see, "G.I. Joe:  The Rise of Cobra" became the choice of compromise.  Despite having played with G.I. Joe toys and watching the cartoon series when I was young, I fully planned to wait for this film to hit the DVD shelves before I watched it.  There just wasn't anything too appealing about it based on the previews.Having now viewed it I must say that it was a pleasant surprise.The plot is rather simple.  In this film, James McCullen (Christopher Eccleston), an arms dealer with a checkered family history, joins forces with a sinister scientist known only as The Doctor (Joseph Gordon-Levitt) and the duo plan to take over the world by threatening it with nanomite weapons.  These weapons can literally eat through metal (and pretty much everything else).  When a convoy of these weapons, led by two soldiers codenamed Duke (Channing Tatum) and Ripcord (Marlon Wayans), is attacked and the nano-weapons are stolen, the international force known as G.I. Joe is sent to retrieve them.From that point on, the film is basically one CGI-laced battle after another.  Fight sequences go from the Joe headquarters to France to the icy waters of the North Pole.  Hand-to-hand combat, "accelerator" suits, ninjas, computerized crossbows, etc. all take center stage as the action spills out on the screen.Like many other big-budget action yarns this film suffers in a number of areas.  Heading the list of things that are wrong with this film is Channing Tatum.  He tries to come across as a leader but instead looks more like a lightweight John Cena (WWE).  Tatum ain't no Duke, and his performance here goes to show that his poor delivery in "Havoc" was no misstep on his part.  Another thing wrong with this film is the fact that it's covered in cheese.  Granted, it's based on a toyline from the 80's, but it would have been nice if the film had been taken a bit more seriously.  Otherwise, the scriptwriters should have gotten rid of some of the strong language and aimed for a more kid-friendly PG rating.I also found that despite the busy nature of the film, it was rather boring at times.  With little character development, it became nothing more than a "that explosion was cool, but wait until you see the next one" series of CGI sequences.There's plenty that's bad about this film, but there is also quite a bit that is good.  As nothing more than an action film, it works wonders.  The CGI does look excellent and the numerous vehicles and weapons that are used in the film turned out great.Although Tatum was miscast as Duke, the majority of the other characters were given decent representations.  Mired in bad one-liners, Dennis Quaid gives a good performance as Hawk.  Christopher Eccleston is sufficient as McCullen/Destro, but much like Quaid he has to swim his way through bad writing.  Rachel Nichols (Scarlett) gives one of the best performances in the film, and Said Taghmaoui is quite enjoyable as Breaker.  Sienna Miller filled out the Baroness' black suit quite well, but her delivery was only average.Other actors who did quite well were Ray Park as the silent and deadly Snake Eyes, Lee Byung-hun as Snake Eyes' arch enemy, Stormshadow and Arnold Vosloo in a small but sinister role as Zartan.Two actors in particular deserve kudos for their performances in this film.  When I first saw that Marlon Wayans was going to portray Ripcord, I immediately smelled a stinky film.  However, Wayans does surprisingly well as the humorous Ripcord.  Deserving even more praise is Joseph Gordon-Levitt.  Although he wasn't perfect as the Doctor/Cobra Commander, he has shown marked improvement from his "Havoc" and "Ten Things I Hate About You" days.  He was a pleasant surprise.There are also a few old faces that pop up.  Director Stephen Sommers reached deep into his "The Mummy" bag and pulled out Vosloo, Brendan Fraser in a cameo role and Kevin J. O'Connor as Dr. Mindbender.  Screen veteran Jonathan Pryce ("Pirates of the Caribbean," "Twelve Monkeys") plays the President of the United States.Overall, "G.I. Joe:  The Rise of Cobra" is a mixed bag of great action sequences and solid individual performances weighed down by a poor choice for a leading man, a dull script and too much focus on the "wow" factor.  If you like pop, sizzle, and bang in your movies, "Joe" is an excellent film to check out.  If you expect your films to develop a little bit more and not rely on CGI to cover up weaknesses, you might want to stay away from "The Rise of Cobra."  Mildly recommended to action fans.  I'll probably buy it once it's been out on DVD awhile and the price goes down.
summary: Lots Of Explosions, Plenty Of Noise, Not Much Else

reviewText: "G.I. Joe: The Rise Of Cobra" is great! This is how the story goes: From the Egyptian desert to deep below the polar ice caps, the elite G.I. JOE team uses the latest in next-generation spy and military equipment to fight the corrupt arms dealer Destro and the growing threat of the mysterious Cobra organization to prevent them from plunging the world into chaos.The cast led by Channing Tatum (as Duke) & Dennis Quaid (as General Hawk) is great! The directing by Stephen Sommers (also produced) (who also wrote and directed "The Mummy" (1999), "The Mummy Returns" (2001) & "Van Helsing" (2004) is great! The story by Sommers, Stuart Beattie (who also wrote the screen story to "Pirates Of The Caribbean: The Curse Of The Black Pearl" (2003), "Collateral" (2004, story & screenplay), "30 Days Of Night" (2007, screenplay) & "Australia" (2008, screenplay) & Michael Gordon (who also wrote the screenplay to "300" (2007) & the screenplay by Beattie, David Elliot & Paul Lovett (both of them wrote the story and screenplay to "Four Brothers" (2005) is great!The music by Alan Silvestri (who also did the music to "The Mummy Returns", "Van Helsing", "Night At The Museum" (2006), "Night At The Museum: Battle Of The Smithsonian" (2009) & the upcoming "A Christmas Carol" (2009) is excellent! The cinematography by Mitchell Amundsen (who also did the cinematography to "Transporter 2" (2005), "Transformers" (2007), "Wanted" (2008) & the upcoming "Jonah Hex" (2010) is excellent! The film editing by Bob Ducsay (also produced) (who also did the film editing to "The Mummy", "The Mummy Returns" (also executive produced) & "Van Helsing" (also produced) & Jim May (who also did the film editing to "Van Helsing" & "The Chronicles Of Narnia: The Lion, The Witch, And The Wardrobe" (2005) is great! The casting by Ronna Kress (who recently did the casting to "G-Force" (2009) is great! The production design by Ed Verreaux (who also did the production design to "Rush Hour 3" (2007) is excellent! The art direction by Chad S. Frey (who also did the art direction to "Rush Hour 3" & the upcoming "The Green Hornet" (2010), Kevin Ishioka (who also did the art direction to the upcoming "Avatar" (2009), Randy Moore (who also did the art direction to "The Curious Case Of Benjamin Button" (2008), Greg Papalia (supervising art director) (who also did the art direction to "Rush Hour 3"), Brad Ricker (who recently did the art direction to "Hotel For Dogs" (2009) & Anne Seibel is excellent! The set decoration by Kate J. Sullivan (who also did the set decoration to "Rush Hour 3") is excellent! The costume design by Ellen Mirojnick (who also did the costume design to "G-Force" & the upcoming "Money Never Sleeps" (2010) is excellent!This is a great action film that keeps you on the edge of your seat. This is a fun, fast-paced ride. This is one of the best action movies of the summer.
summary: "G.I. Joe: The Rise Of Cobra" is great!

reviewText: I was shocked after viewing this film that it had received such negative reviews. If you had high expectations like I did, for the summer flick WOLVERINE ORGINS and was sent crashing down, then give this film a try. IT KICKS MAJOR BUTT. There is non-stop action, in many ways it's like X-MEN meets STAR WARS meets LEAGUE OF EXTRODINARY GENTLEMEN. I was blown away by this film. Are you getting the picture that I actually liked it? First of all for being based on a toy franchise and a cartoon, this film exceeds expectations. It is melodramatic, cheesey in some aspects but when it comes down to it you have to been an idiot to realize that it makes the movie that much more fun to watch. Dennis Quaid gives a very hammed up performance as the commander or general, of the Joes. Everytime he spoke I couldn't help but smile to myself. The actress who played the Baroness was by far my favorite. For you parents who might be considering this film for your kids. There is some very low mild language. I think the worse that I actually heard or was made to notice is the word p*ssed off. There is an incredible amout of action violence but if you have already let the kids see SPIDERMAN, X-MEN, STAR WARS EPISODE III, then you should feel safe showing them this film. In some aspect I feel that this film could grow to be a cult classic. As far as the storyline, there are actually a few suprises that I did not see coming. I strongly hope that this will get a much-deserved sequel. I will be buying this dvd and actually a few copies more for Christmas gifts. DON'T MISS OUT!!!!
summary: Clearly one of the best movies of the summer.

reviewText: "G.I. Joe", much like last years"Transformers"sequel, is an action film of the most common denominator. It's bright, flashy, loud, occasionally obnoxious and rife with eye-rolling stabs at inducing laughter. Yet whereas "Transformers" could be genuinely funny, "G.I. Joe" seems painfully unaware that its attempts at crowd pleasing humor almost always fall flat. For starters, the two leads are grossly miscast. Channing Tatum, who portrays Duke, is the lesser offender. Though he certainly looks the part of a square-jawed All-American soldier, he's among the most wooden actors I've ever seen in a massive-budget Hollywood blockbuster. Eternal twelve year old Leonardo DiCaprio could act circles around this guy, and that's saying something! But though Tatum may be lacking in versatility and range, he makes up for these shortcomings in that he's a likeable enough fellow. So much so that I wouldn't mind a whit seeing Tatum star in a sequel. Besides, let's face it, a film based off a toy line and Saturday morning cartoon doesn't exactly require Daniel Day Lewis types.By far the worst component here is Marlon Wayans as Ripcord. Considering the character is intended as comic relief and a foil to Duke's more straight-laced gung-ho soldiering, I can understand the producers felt compelled to cast someone with a background in comedy. Unfortunately, Wayans is as hammy as a club sandwich and a terrible actor to boot. Despite a packed theatre, nearly every one of his flimsy jabs at humor failed miserably (though one joke in particular, uttered when Duke proposed to Ana, elicited a fair amount of laughs). The dialog exchanges between Duke and Ripcord is b-movie quality weak, particularly at the beginning of the film. The bulk of their banter is composed of jokes we've heard many times before, jokes that were lame the first time told. This exchange is particularly weak:Ripcord: "You know Duke, I've been thinking..."Duke: "What have I told you about that?"Ripcord: "...I've already submitted an application."Duke: "They take those in crayon?"The one clever, nearly hilarious joke involving Ripcord actually has nothing to do with Wayans' performance. When donning his advanced Delta 6 suit, he's told the equipment has integrated artificial intelligence that will respond to whatever he's thinking. Instantly, images of Scarlett (who Ripcord is deeply attracted to), flash across his helmet visor. But that's the one solid moment of humor, otherwise this goofy interpretation of Ripcord is one of the films weakest points, and though he'll probably be a hit with children, for anyone older than twelve he'll come across as naught but irritating.The action setpieces, which are certainly the main draw of "G.I. Joe", are absolutely flawless. So much so that this was my fourth favorite action-oriented film released last year. The majority of those who didn't enjoy the film either didn't see the trailer or were under some sort of strange impression they were going to see an Oscar contender. The straight action is sole reason to see this film. The two best, most memorable action sequences include an excellent assault on the Joes headquarters and a lighting-fast race to save the Eiffel Tower from the nefarious Baroness and Storm Shadow. Most of the Joe favorites are here, including: Snake Eyes, Scarlett, Destro, Cobra Commander, Cover Girl, Zartan, General Hawk, and Heavy Duty among others. Each one of these characters is well cast and even resemble their cartoon counterparts quite well (particularly Dennis Quaid as General Hawk and Sienna Miller as the Baroness).I appreciate, however, that the crew didn't feel it vital to strictly adhere to the comic book and cartoon interpretations of these characters. Had they done that, the Zartan character would almost assuredly look hilariously absurd! I've noticed many reviewers have complained that there's "too many" characters, but that's part of the fun of a film adaptation of comic book material like G.I. Joe or"X-Men". If anything, I found myself wanting to see more characters, and cannot wait to see the new ones that will feature in the sequel. The G.I. Joe universe has a host of novel players to utilize, including my personal favorites Shipwreck, Gung Ho, Dial Tone, Flint, and Dusty. Will any of those feature in the sequel? Time will tell.One of the producers, prior to the release, stated that all the futuristic technology featured in the film (including the nearly invisible camoflage clothing and variants of the Delta 6 suits) was a mere ten to twenty years away from being reality. This is true for the most part, adding a small dose of authenticity to what is, admittedly, a very silly testosterone-fueled explosion-fest. The most prominent technological fantasy invention would have to be Destro's missiles which feature sophisticated nanotechnology. Speaking of fantastical inventions, one of the most bizarre scenes is when Breaker attempts to use a device to read the final thoughts of a deceased baddie. He jabs two poles into the corpse's head and uses a cell phone sized device to attempt to scan the dying memories. As if that isn't enough, we watch as the body rather gruesomely decomposes in mere seconds due to a self-termination device implanted in him, also using the same nanomites the missiles use.There are numerous flashback sequences between Duke and the Baroness and between Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow that add a modicum of depth to the story. The Snake Eyes/Storm Shadow feud goes way back to the comic books, though here (perhaps in the interest of time) it's reduced to something much more simplistic. I'm not well versed in G.I. Joe canon, so I don't know if it's been previously established that Duke and the Baroness had a relationship, but its a great story element to help tie the characters together. There's even a grand flashback piece at the very beginning of the film that adds some intrigue to Destro's story. The pace of the film is never ruined by these flashback scenes, which is a difficult feat to be certain. As the film's byline states, this is the "Rise of Cobra", so I hope that in the sequel we get to see an entrenched, organized Cobra military as opposed to the mostly freelance gang of mercenaries featured in this film.Ultimately, "G.I. Joe" will not be remembered as a great film, but I feel genuine pity for someone who cannot watch a film such as this and simply have a great time. The plot is typically simplistic, involving the tried-and-true "protect the valuable object" scenario we've seen in countless other recent films (such as"Eragon"and"Babylon A.D.", off the top of my head). Still, though the story may not be terribly complex, it's well told and doesn't detract. Well, except perhaps for one of the final scenes, in which Cobra Commander and Destro don goofy-looking helmets and share an evil cackle together. Yes, Mr. Screenwriter, as much as we appreciated the numerous nods to the classic cartoons, some things should've been left in those cartoons. Hopefully in the sequel we'll see a more involving tale, because even though this film may be explicitly targeted at the young, a handful of blockbusters have proved general audiences can handle a slightly more complicated story, such as"Mission Impossible"or"The Dark Knight".I feel it prudent to stress again that, at times, "G.I. Joe" is nearly unbearably stupid. Keep in mind that the film is merely a vehicle for exciting action sequences, and as that, it's an absolute success. Those sequences are tight, frenetic and well choreographed. This is, of course, the primary reason one should see the film to begin with. More than that, it's a memorable film, which is more than I can say for some recent action flicks such as"Bangkok Dangerous"or"The Spirit". In summation: if you have a hearty appetite for action and are willing to shut off your brain for two hours, there's not a single dull moment in "G.I. Joe".
summary: Knowing is, indeed, half the battle. . .

reviewText: When this movie first came out, there were several complaints about this being an Anti American movie. I couldn't believe it because if there was any movie that is pro America I would think it'd be GI JOE The All American Hero! Having watched the film, I can now see their point. It wasn't anti american, but there was a coldness to the film. The dark body outfits, the lack of display for the American flag, recruiting members from around the globe rather than using America's Finest soldiers... it seemed to stray from the original concept. Films are increasingly becoming way too dependent on CGI and having futuristic advanced technology in storylines to push a film, and its a shame. The storylines are suffering as a result. I also have to say the acting in this film is as bad as other reviewers state. ITs watchable, but there are cringe worthy moments. Not entirely the fault of the actors though since the dialogue throughout the film is too simplistic. I never watched the cartoon series, but I have to say the most interesting characters in the film were the ninja characters, Storm Shadow and Snake Eyes. I did enjoy their childhood flashbacks and if this film gets a sequel, Id like to see them play bigger roles. As a kid, I do remember the Baroness character being much more devilish, stronger and having more of a dominant presence than this horrible choice of an actress picked for this film. Its like they recruited actors from The Hills to play these parts. In spite of all the complaints, it was still something Id watch again just for the sake of having something to watch. I was entertained and its a good action movie for anyone who's into action films.
summary: Okay movie, but it didn't feel like "The American Hero"

reviewText: I admit it.  I likes me some comic book movies and some video game movies (Iron Man and Resident Evil come to mind). I even likes me some kids toy movies (see Transformers).  They're good fun, escapist entertainment.  This movie was nothing more than a rip off of every recently released special effects blockbuster with much lower quality effects.  Remember how cheesy Daredevil was.  It's like that, only with the most painfully stupid scene I have ever witnessed in a movie.  Towards the end of the film, the villians blew up the ice on the surface of the ocean, whereupon the ice came crashing down to the bottom of the sea.  I'm all for willing suspension of disbelief, but if you are going to have magic ice that sinks like a rock, you gotta give me a reason to buy it.  Hasn't everyone on the planet seen the ice in their glass floating on the top.  Gotta go.  I'm feeling nauseous from the memory.
summary: You know that great movie Transformers?  It's not like that.

reviewText: I should break this up into two sections:1.) The Blu Ray review (quality of the movie)2.) Brief Movie review (just a quick take on it)First off, the Blu Ray of this movie is awesome!  Crystal clear, great sound and smooth.  Loved it on my plasma TV, but it looks even better on my friends LCD screen.  The scenes literally come off the screen and he does not have 3D on the TV!  Get this Blu Ray!  It deserves room on your shelf.Next, a quick review of the movie itself.I went to see this in the theater expecting it to be total trash and very surprised.  It's pure fun and very entertaining.  It delivers, period.  Yes, it has a few corny lines, but people, this is an fun action movie, not a love story, not a serious drama or theater.  You see this to have some fun.  I suspect there are many GI Joe fans that felt disappointed by this movie because they haven't grown up yet.  Yes those people that still have their action figures, the GI Joe underwear, or the action figure with the kung fu grip (ok that one is cool) and probably went to this movie looking for a serious GI Joe movie.  Come on!  Grow up!For example, the entire action sequence in France was a blast in the movie theater and great on Blu Ray with surround sound!  The whole movie is just plain fun with great action, special effects and good imagination.Is it perfect?  Hell no!  It's no Blade Runner or Empire Strikes Back, but what it is is just pure entertainment.  It has a high replay value and if you are a fan of action movie, this Blu Ray deserves room on your shelf.And if you don't like it, then sell your copy on Ebay and go back to watching the old Gi Joe cartoons while being wrapped up in your GI Joe blanket, in your GI Joe underwear and have Mommy tuck you in with a Kung Fu Grip shot to the head ;-)Really, just relax and enjoy the movie for what it is...fun!I do hope that they keep the same actors and director for the next release and can't wait to see it!  They need to continue it.Peace out everyone!

reviewText: I have been sitting here, looking at a blank page for several minutes.  I don't even know where to begin with this absolute horror show of a movie. reviewText: Movie makers are always looking for sources to create films from. More so than that, they're looking for movies that can become franchises, turning a single film into a multi-million dollar money making machine. Sometimes they do so at the cost of a good film resulting in the franchise dying. Other times they make a movie that does so well, that hits all the right notes, that they have a sure fire hit. Such is the case with G.I.JOE: THE RISE OF COBRA.Based on what was first a toy from Hasbro and then a hit TV cartoon series, the creators here led by director Stephen Sommers (of THE MUMMY fame) have transformed those original ideas into a fantastic action film. When the term pulse pounding action is used, this is the movie you should think of.The film opens in the past with a weapons developer and a look at the McCullen clan founder whose current descendant James (Christopher Eccleston) has just turned over a new weapon to U.N. This weapon uses nanomites, nearly invisible robots, to destroy and eat metal. Leading the convoy transporting the weapons is a top Special Forces team led by Duke (Channing Tatum).Attacked by a secret villainous team led by the Baroness (Sienna Miller), an ex-flame of Duke, the team (or what's left of it) is rescued by an elite group known as G.I. Joe, led by General Hawk (Dennis Quaid). Sticking with his orders, Duke and fellow team mate Ripcord (Marlon Wayans) stay with their package.Arriving at the Joe's secret headquarters, they request to join the team and are given the chance once it becomes known Duke knows the Baroness. After a brief training period, they become part time members. But a tracking device on the weapons case switched on by McCullen has led his team to the Joe base and they attack using both special operatives infected with the nanomites and martial arts expert Storm Shadow (Byun-hung Lee) with the Baroness.The weapons taken, Gen. Hawk wounded, the team goes into full blown rescue mode as they track the weapons to France. With the help of super powered armor that enhances all abilities (as well as containing some high tech fire power), the team tries to reclaim the weapons before they can be used. They fail and (as seen in previews) the Eiffel Tower falls.With only one chance left to recapture the weapons and take on this new enemy, later to be called Cobra, the team sets out to save the world. Will they make it in time? Will they have sufficient weapons to do so? Does the sun rise in the east?This movie is a blast. It takes the toys so many were fond of playing with (for my age 12" tall jointed clod hoppers, for the younger set 6" tall characters with names and multiple weapons) and brings them to life on the screen. It makes those many minutes of animated cells seen by so many for so long come to life and appear in full color action, blasting their way across the screen.The story is simple. Good guy versus bad guy. To make it complete we get background segments that explain who these characters are, fleshing them out further than the cartoons had time for. Duke and the Baroness, Cobra Commander and Duke, and everyone's favorite, Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow. There pieces give us a full fledged story to wrap all the action around.But it is the action that takes center stage here. This is a definite popcorn flick determined to keep you cheering for the good guys and hissing the bad. Underwater battles, snow covered terrains, secret lairs in the Sahara and enough rough and ready heroes to make the world seem a safer place.More than anything this movie is about having fun. It makes it a film that all ages can enjoy as opposed to playing too much to the young, or overdoing the adult thing for parents. Unlike the cartoon, people do die here and when shot fall down for good. But not to the point of glorifying the violence or lingering on it. Think Lone Ranger in the 50's type violence.Having seen the movie twice, in the theater and now on DVD, I can't recommend it enough. It's not just one that you'll want to rent, but one you'll want to add to your collection. Myself, I determine that by if I think I'd watch it again. This is a movie to be viewed over and over and have fun with again and again.

reviewText: Watching G.I. Joe I expected it to be horrible. Mainly because I never heard anyone talking about it and what I did hear wasn't very good. Then I realized that these people probably were never fans of the show I grew up on as a kid. They probably went in expecting to see something like Star Wars or Batman for all I know. None of the 1 star reviews I saw on here even mentioned anything about the adaption from the Cartoon to the live action movie. For me sitting back after all these years and seeing a live action G.I. Joe movie on screen was pretty exciting. Although this movie didn't have some of my favorite characters that I remember I.E.(Lady Jane) it was still pretty awsome.Watching G.I. Joe was just like watching the cartoon. There was always some rediculous over the top scheme Cobra was planning, and the Joe's always had some rediculous and over the top way of stopping them. The vehicles, the weaponry, the action... it was all here! They even used the "lazer" bullet effects and sounds! I really couldn't imagine how they would take all the action from the Cartoon and bring it to the silver screen but they did just that. I was worried they would "Hollywoodize" the crazy schemes of Cobra but they didn't. The plot revolved around the strong concept of deception with a bigger scheme behind it...which is what Cobra mostly did.I was very pleased with the overall movie, but what kind of took away from it was a few of the choice actors. Well... I take that back... just one! "DUKE" who ever they hired for that role didn't belong in the movie. He had absolutely no emotion for the character of Duke and was 1 dimensional. He was completely flat, and didn't belong in a film like this. It was a very poor casting decision and it showed. You don't pick an actor like that to play one of the greatest heroes/lead characters in the G.I. Joe franchise. I hated having to watch the scenes featuring him because his acting ruined the movie.The other characters that steal the show are the Baroness,Snake Eyes,and RipCord. In the movie Ripcord had a big role, but I don't remember him that much from the show. The Baroness was the cherry on the cake and Snake Eyes(my favorite character from the show) is what made me watch this in the first place. There were alot of people from the Joe team missing that I hope we'll see in the next film.Overall this was a good movie and I think it doesn't get the respect that it deserves. G.I. Joe the live movie did a good job modeling the cartoon and I'm glad the directors didn't try to change that. They brought me a G.I. Joe similar to the one I remember. I just can't wait till they make the 2nd film and we get to see GI.Joe vs. Cobra for real this time.
summary: I'm glad I didn't let the critics stop me!

reviewText: I went to see G.I. Joe yesterday. Joe sports an impressive cast (of cameo stars) including:Jonathan Pryce as the President of The United StatesBrendan Fraser as a G.I. Joe instructorArnold Vosloo as Zartanand Kevin O'Connor as a scientist3 of those 4 were in the first two Mummy movies directed by G.I. Joe's Stephen Sommers.The movie itself was full of special effects. Joe's villain decides to use nanonites to eat away cities in order to rule the world.It's up to Dennis Quaid's team of Joes to stop them.The ending has some nice twists to it and sets up the rest of the series - you know the sequel is already being written.

reviewText: I rented GI Joe having fairly low expectations for the movie.  Being a fan of the cartoon from my childhood, I at least wanted to see the new attempt at the franchise.First of all, the acting is horrendous, even when you factor in the macho/roided out nature of the characters.  Of course, the cast is a collection of C-list stars, so you can't expect too much out of them.  I would have been happy if they had all made like Snake-Eyes and stayed silent, especially Wayans.The action is almost too-fast. I barely had time to register what was going on.  One minute the new Joes are training, the next they're being attacked at their base, then they're running around Paris.  Combined with all their flashy gadgets, the pace was bewildering.  And in between these rushes of action were these half-conceived, afterthought backstories on a few of the major characters, mostly Duke & the Baroness, and then Snake-Eyes & Storm Shadow.  I know the first movie in a series is supposed to establish some backstories, but for GI Joe, it was hastily done and incomplete.  The team was already together with no explanation of how the team was even conceived, funded, how the team was put together, etc.  I felt like the movie picked up in the middle instead of the beginning.There was just too much cheesiness to the story, and that's saying a lot for a movie based on a toy & cartoon.  The producers were obviously cashing in on the franchise name and appeal to kids from the 80's instead of trying to put together even a decent action movie.  Just not a well thought out or well executed concept.Very disappointing considering what the movie could have been.

reviewText: As a writer, it's always instructive to watch a poorly written movie and to analyze what went wrong.Oh, maybe I'm being too hard on G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra, a retelling of the cartoon I enjoyed as a kid, which itself was a rehash of an older entertainment franchise.  I mean, I did say to my wife, "Let's watch something mindless," and I got what I wanted.Still, I can't help wondering if the movie makers intended for me to burst out laughing the first time the Baroness walks onto the screen looking like Sarah Palin in a skin suit.  Nor can I help wondering if, when the movie was finished, I was supposed to admit that I couldn't remember the main character's name.Somewhere between the underwater space battle, the ninja swordfight over the pit of crackling electrical arcs, and the evil doctor talking through a mask, I finally realized that this movie aspired to be Star Wars and failed miserably.  And I think the problem can be summed up in one elementary topic of story craft: character development.  Sure, I believe the original Star Wars had lots of revolutionary special effects for the time, and that's what all of us kids buzzed about as we ran around our lawns with our X-Wings making "pew!  pew!" laser gun sounds.  But I also remember being fascinated with the character dynamics.  By the end of Star Wars, I felt like I knew Luke, Han, Darth Vader, Chewbacca, and C-3PO as well as members of my own family.  I never forgot their names.  Interest in where these characters were headed (and, of course, the cool special effects) brought me back for The Empire Strikes Back sequel. When the simulated space battles on the front lawn were done for the day, we sat down for long philosophical discussions about Darth Vader's revelation that he was Luke's father.G.I. Joe had all the ingredients of a great story like Star Wars, but they were undercooked and underseasoned.  The writers tried to establish character dynamics through the use of flashbacks rather than to let the present story do the work.  Characters contrivedly addressed each other by their names ("yes, we will work on that next, Storm Shadow") so the audience would learn those (corny) names and/or connect them to their previous cartoon incarnations rather than to let this information come out more naturally.The cinematography didn't help.  The frenetic, herky-jerky camera work made me nauseous at the same time that it prevented me from even understanding what was going on.  You don't need to move and shake the camera to film a good fight scene, you really don't, not unless the actors are so bereft of athleticism that you need to cover up their shortcomings.  (Yes, I'm talking to you, David Carradine, in the latter years of Kung Fu.)  Please, just pan back a little, and let me follow the action like a normal human being and not like someone flipping through comic book panels in fast motion.  Also, it's okay, really it is, to let a single camera angle last for more than two seconds.  I won't get bored, I promise.Maybe I'm just getting old.  Maybe I should just pull up the A&E; channel and watch a black-and-white adventure story from the 1940s.  The characterizations in those are usually outstanding.  And because the directors no doubt were raised in the theater, the camera angles are always a good ten feet away from the subject, as if to film the events on a stage.  (The actors always shouted their lines, too, so those of us the back of the movie theater could hear.  Yes, I admit some things have improved in movie-making.)Sigh.  If only Hollywood would hire me.

reviewText: "G.I. Joe: Rise of Cobra" provides big, loud, dumb, silly fun. It's a "bad" movie, but a "bad" movie that is entertaining. I would have given it a two-star overall, but the fun quotient it provides in a rather lackluster summer bumps it up to three.It's like a live-action version of the cartoon, and it's good that the filmmaker doesn't take it too seriously.At the same time, it's good that they do try to provide some bits of character development and exposition, although they try a little bit too hard, especially with some flashback scenes that fall short.But, that's a small quibble, as the movie's a fun action-blast of a ride from beginning to end.By contrast, Transformers Revenge of the Fallen was dumb -- and awful. G.I. Joe is dumb and silly, but for fans of the cartoon, it's more in line with that 80s show and the whole movie is delivered with tongue firmly in cheek.But if someone sits down to analyze the acting, the character development and preposterous, yet interesting storyline, they're going to hate this movie.This is a fun, entertaining piece of junk that entertains on pure adrenaline, goofy bits and lame one-liners.Marlon Wayans is his typical annoying self, yet still fun at times, the female leads (Rachel Nichols and Sienna Miller) are good-looking as Scarlett and the Baroness, and Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow are ultra-cool.One thing that did surprise me -- aside from it being a fun two hours -- was the violence. They really lived up to that PG-13 rating. Unlike the cartoon, where no one bites the bullet (or, er, the laser), there are some graphic death scenes and all sorts of violence, maiming and graphic fatal, close-up gun shots to the head and other body parts, even some impalings. That did lend the movie some gravitas. Just had to let you all know, and knowing's half the battle.Yo Joe! :)

reviewText: I was pleasantly surprised by how entertaining this film was.  I liked it a lot more than any of the Transformer movies and the movie never seemed to get boring.  It begins with a Scottish arms dealer caught in 1600's France being forced to wear a steel mask (which is literally burnt into his head).  We then flash forward to what is labelled "the near distant future." and the arm's dealer's later descendent is now a heavy dealer to the US military (and to other unsavory characters as well).A contingent of soldiers is delivering a bunch of nanoweapons capable of eating anything in their patch (including steel, concrete, etc) when they are set upon by high tech and seemingly unstoppable enemies led by a mysterious woman with long black hair.  Two of the soldiers are able to escape and are later captured by the GI Joes which is a covert operation headed by Dennis Quaid.  The soldiers talk their way into joining the Joes, especially since one of the soldiers was engaged to the mysterious woman attacker and may know enough about her to capture her.The movie continues with unbelievable technology close to Star Wars type with super soldier suits and incredible planes and underwater vehicles.  There is also a rivalry between the evil kung fu assassin with the bad guys and the Joe's own kung fu warrior.  Apparently the two were rivals from the time they were boys and each wants to kill the other.If you can ignore the obvious logic flaws (how can all the technology be financed, how come the soldier in the super soldier suits can run as fast as cars and not get tired, etc.) and sit back and just watch you will be highly entertained throughout and the action is virtually non-stop.  This movie was way better than expected.  But is is still far inferior to the new Star Trek film.

reviewText: ...But it is a fun ride, as a kid "G.I.Joe" was my favorite thing next to "Star Wars" & I at a mere 12 & 13 read the comics, they were quite story-oriented with an ongoing story arc, as was the 1983/1984 cartoon, the characters were colorful & each had their distinct personalities, as did the "Cobra" villians, but let's be real people, you can't do a on-going comic-book story in a two hour movie, however this film like most summer films is one big shoot-em up/explosion fest that has little character developement, which didn't bother me because I was already familiar with the characters to begin with below are the good & bad things about this one...The Good>>>>The action was awesome, definately an assault on the senses!!The cast>>>Ray Park(Darth Maul) as "Snake Eyes, they couldn't have picked a better personRachel Nichols(P2) as "Scarlett, man we have got to see more of her!!!!Sienna Miller as "Baroness, always pictured Catherine Zeta Jones in this role, but Miller is a good alternate, & she is also one we need to see more of..Channing Tatum as "Duke" was good, always pictured Rutger Hauer(Blade Runner)in this role, but sadly he is now showing his age, so Tatum is o.k. in this, even though I have no idea who he isThe actor playing "Heavy Duty" can't pronounce his name, but he was Mr. Ecko on the hit show "Lost", he is good here as well, he was also in director Stephen Sommers "Mummy Returns"The one playing "Storm Shadow" was very true to the characterMarlon Wayans was also fun as the comic relief...& Dennis Quaid was well... Dennis Quaid who looked nothing like "Hawk"which brings me to...The Bad>>>>Cobra Commander was always a mystery, no one, not even Destro & Baroness knew who he was, here the viewer knows at the end, well.... so much for the suspense factorDestro is reduced to a "Batman" villian who becomes Destro, never happened in the comics, but his involvement with Baroness was in the comicsBaroness' past involvement with Duke never happened in the comics, but that did not bother me, her repent at the end I can only hope is just a ploy to spring Destro & Cobra Commander at the begining of the next film... Sienna Miller said she signed a three-picture deal as did everyone else I am sureArnold Vosloo as Zartan was o.k., but him killing "Cover Girl"... WTF!!!!!!!!Dennis Quaid got no action scenes... at all!!!& "Storm Shadow's fate is unknown, surely they didn't kill him offmany other favorites(Flash, Major Bludd, Ace,.. not here>>> probably because they will be introduced in the next film....& where was Agent Helix??? did I miss her, please help me on this, after seeing the action figure I was excited to see who would be playing her, but she was MIA!!!!overall, this was a cool film if you didn't set your expectations high, did it go against the comics??  yes & no!but let's face it, Hollywood sells what people want & that is a dumbing down to the masses, people can argue character developement all they want, but most do not want that, evidence of this can be seen in the constant trashing of the "Star Wars" Prequels" , just like with the new "Star Trek" everyone seems to like it, but had it been like the 60's show which relied on the strength of it's characters, everyone would have hated it, so the new film is one big action fest unlike the previous "Trek" films, so it should come as no surprise why "G.I.Joe" is this way as well, the comics were character driven, the film is not simply because the masses don't want character driven films, partly the reason this one didn't disappoint me, I knew that going in, & when you take these facts into account, than this one will be a fun ride!!!
summary: You can't go in with high expectations on this one.....

reviewText: So what do you get from a movie based on a toy product..?  Well, characters which get thrown around and stepped on in much the way their toy counterparts do..  Stephen Sommers, director of The Mummy, creates here a cgi heavy action thriller based on an elite team of soldiers, called G.I. Joes.  When a nanotechnology based warhead is stolen, they spring in to action to recover it.By all rights, this could have been pretty awful.  The cgi has that look about it where you're constantly reminded what you are watching is not real, removing any sense of jeopardy for the characters.  There's a nagging feeling as you watch characters in motorised suits do leaps and jumps or planes flying past the speed of sound zip off in a different direction, that the movie is just not quite obeying the laws of physics... On the other hand, several elements save the movie from mediocrity.  The action scenes that do not involve, or at least involve less cgi, are actually pretty impressive.  Carnage on the streets of Paris involves both the annoyingly unconvincing aforementioned suits, but a fair deal of genuine car carnage which is pleasurable to watch.  Even a few set piece cgi scenes have a wow factor, like the climax to the Paris scene.  Then there is the actors, who do a good job of making the ridiculous.. well, maybe not believable, but acceptable.  Then there's an infectious sense of fun and not taking themselves too seriously that serves the movie well.  This is not a Batman style dark adaptation, but a lively and colourful imagining of what sort of world a G.I. Joe could inhabit.  While Dennis Quaid has little screen time and even then just has to grin at the camera and bark a few commands, the rest of the cast manage to cram a heap of backstory into the movie without the film ever collapsing in on itself under the need to explain everything.  Somewhat bizarrely, there are a heap of references and similarities to Star Wars plotlines and scenes, from a black masked heavy breathing villain, to underwater fights which look remarkably like the attack on the death star, and even duels which may as well have been with light sabres to complete the effect.So with a music score full of zest by Alan Silvestri, aided by a brilliant and clear transfer to Bluray in both sight and sound, this is a brash, action packed, disposable movie even.. but good fun, for all that.

reviewText: For what it's worth, this is a fun movie to watch if you want some mindless entertainment. It's not going to win any Oscars that's for sure. The script is brutal, the acting more than occasionally cringe worthy, and the plot full of as many holes as a spaghetti strainer. However there are some great action sequences, as a sort of pervasive comic book fun that makes the whole thing better than the sum of its parts. Most of the characters are pretty one dimensional, and the few that aren't aren't given enough time to develop. I thought the most interesting characters were Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow, and their various confrontations made for the best moments in the entire film. They could have done so much more with that storyline than they did. It would have been more interesting to have Storm Shadow redeemed at the end than the boring girl friend character.The Joes being some sort of multi-nation peace keepers instead of "Real American Heroes" put a bad taste in my mouth. Is it so bad to have American Heroes these days that we have to turn it into a badass version of NATO?The powered exoskeletons were ripped right out of CRYSIS. They look almost identical. The undersea base of COBRA looked like a rip-off of BIOSHOCK. This is definitely a movie heavily influenced by video games and marketed to the same demographic. Nothing wrong with that--it's actually A LOT better than 90% of movies based on video games.Despite some pretty glaring flaws, the movie is pretty entertaining. I went in with pretty low expectations, and ended up enjoying it more than I thought I would. Don't expect too much from RISE OF COBRA, and you just might enjoy it too.2.5/5 Stars. Silly but fun.

reviewText: Can anyone truly be surprised?  From the moment it was announced that Stephen Sommers (The Mummy, Van Helsing) would be helming it and all through its production, just about everyone knew that the live-action adaptation of G.I. Joe would more than likely be incredibly bad.  And boy oh boy, whoever would have thought that it could be so bad.  If you thought that the universally-panned Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen was bad, you haven't seen anything yet until you view G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra.  Soldier buddies Duke (Channing Tatum) and Ripcord (Marlon Wayans) get drawn into the world of the elite unit known as G.I. Joe to take on Duke's old flame Baroness (the gorgeous Sienna Miller) and "Destro" McCullen (Christopher Eccleston) as their criminal organization Cobra seeks world domination.  Along for the ride are familiar Joe and Cobra characters like General Hawk (Dennis Quaid), Snake Eyes (Ray Park), Scarlett (Rachel Nichols), Storm Shadow (Byung-hun Lee), Heavy Duty (Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje), Breaker (Said Taghmaoui), Zartan (Arnold Vosloo), Dr. Mindbender (Sommers regular Kevin J. O'Connor), Cover Girl (Karolina Kurkova), and an all too-brief (and seriously maligned) Cobra Commander (Joseph Gordon-Levitt) who is referred to here as "The Doctor".  While this is an origin story at its heart, there are just too many over-the-top ridiculous moments that you have to see to believe.  Not to mention some poor CGI effect sequences, stale action scenes, lame costumes, and some incredibly poor acting (particularly from Tatum as Duke), and the end result is this train wreck of a film.  Other than the fact that Sienna Miller looks great in tight leather, there aren't any true redeeming values to find with G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra.  Even the most die hard fan of Hasbro's toyline will have a hard time getting any sort of enjoyment out of this wreck, and in the end, the best thing for any and all to do, is just pretend it doesn't even exist, which may get harder to do once the inevitable sequels rear their ugly heads.
